 But I ain't finished, I'm devoted

tate_text:
Kanye is operating as a musician in the best possible time.



By using both technical ability in the production of his beats and his plain musicianship, West is easily keepin' it going with album after album of hits. He’s definitely doin' it.

 I have an early meeting out of town
 
 [ELIZA]
 It’s still dark outside
tate_text:
Hamilton doesn’t tell Eliza what he is going to do. Considering the Hamilton family’s track record with duels, you’d think he would be smarter.

“Out of town” refers to, as with Philip’s duel, the duel across the river in Weehawken, New Jersey where “everything is legal”.

As agreed in “Your Obedient Servant”, the duel will begin at dawn, hence, Hamilton’s need to leave before the sun is up.

tate_text:
Kanye previously rapped about designing his own hotel on “Clique.” Considering his success in the fashion world and the profitability potential of hotels, a Kanye Hotel might be a good idea.

In a recent edition of Ye’s infamous Twitter rants, he tweeted out a chart he had put together for his creative initiative: DONDA.  Under the “Hospitality” section, his first item listed is “Hotels”.

ref_text: 'Cause it's my business, God as my witness
tate_text:
Ariana relies on herself and trusts her own decisions, regardless of what others might think.

Using God as a “witness” to swear that something is true has a long Biblical tradition. In 2014, Ariana left the Roman Catholic church and converted to Kabbalah, a form of Jewish mysticism also practiced by Madonna. She said that she decided to leave Catholicism because it rejected her brother, who is gay:

When my brother was told that God didn’t love him I was like, ‘OK, that’s not cool.’ They were building a Kabbalah centre in Florida so we both checked it out and really had a connection with it.

ref_text: And since birth I've been cursed with this curse to just curse
tate_text:
Sometimes it’s like Em has coprolalia (involuntary profanity, which actually only affects about 10% of those with Tourette’s sydrome).

But relative to his hip-hop peers, Em is no exception. Rap Analytics scanned “10,000 songs from over 150 artists between 1987-2013” and compared a “rapper’s total word count with how much profanity they’ve laced into their bars” and found Em to be “middle of the pack”.

And if you can believe Em’s mom, “Marshall rarely swore in conversation.”

ref_text:
I can see
 Your defense mechanism is my decision
 Knock these walls down, that’s my religion
tate_text:
Lamar uses the term “religion” here literally. In 2013, he declared on-stage that he had recently undergone baptism. In many Protestant churches, baptism is a symbol of willing acceptance of the “saving grace” of Jesus Christ, and a public affirmation of faith.

“Knock these walls down” is likely a reference to the religious biblical story of “the walls of Jericho”, a story in which Israelites marched around the walls until they fell down through their faith in God.

Lamar has credited God’s favor as the reason he was able to escape his rough upbringing. He believes his career is divinely inspired, and that he was called to “a greater purpose.”

God put something in my heart to get across and that’s what I’m going to focus on, using my voice as an instrument and doing what needs to be done.

ref_text:
Though I wish he were here instead
 Don't want that living in your head
 He just comes to visit me
 When I'm dreaming every now and then (And then)
tate_text:
This verse follows a similar theme from the August 2018 Sweetener track, “R.E.M” where Ariana alludes to meeting a boy in her dreams:

Last night, boy, I met you, yeah
When I was asleep (sleep)
You’re such a dream to me, mmm, woah

Fans believe this is a homage to the late Mac Miller, who dated Ariana from August 2016 to May 2018 and passed away in September 2018. After he passed, Ariana struggled with feelings for him while she was engaged to Pete, which may have led to their breakup.

This line also sounds similar to Mac’s verse on September 2016’s “Cinderella,” a song he wrote about her:

You in my dreams, that’s why I sleep all the time"

This was even a line she tweeted in late 2018.

Grande has displayed a deep emotional bond to Mac. She wrote a song titled “reMeMber,” that ultimately didn’t make it on the album because Ariana felt the song was too personal.

 If I fell in love with you before I ever even knew
 I catch your eye then look away as if it never happened

tate_text: Love at first sight is an idiom. There are examples of this present in the bible, leading some to believe that love at first sight is a result of predestination or divine intervention. Western society idolizes this idea, since the majority of the population identify as followers of Christianity. Cole’s criticism can be seen as frustration with how people act when the topic is brought up, acting as if it’s “romantic”—even though he may be attracted to a girl at first sight, he knows it isn’t love.

ref_text: And just as I go to walk out of my bedroom door
tate_text:
Eminem is watching a dream, but he converts the dream to his real life. As at that time he was the best-selling artist and was also at the top of the game too. He has mentioned the problems regarding fame in “The Way I Am”.

Eminem doesn’t get enough time for his family so whenever he tries to tell them that he loves them very much, his “Fame” and his alter-ego “Slim Shady” are such “Monsters” that don’t let him do this. He is busy all the time recording songs. There are also concerts in different parts of the world which he has to attend of course he cannot disappoint his fans. This was also a reason which caused problem in his marriage with his wife “Kim”.

Now he is in his bedroom thinking that he should tell his family that he loves them. As he goes to leave the bedroom, the dream he suddenly realizes that he is in a concert in Sweden, which once again brings the theme, the background and also the main point of the song is revealed here. He doesn’t change the dream himself, the dream changes around him. This is because he feels he has no control over the actions.

This is further explained in the fourth single “The Monster” off his 8th Studio album “The Marshall Mathers Lp2”.

Through flouting the Maxim of Quantity (speaking less or more than is required of the discourse), Hamilton is shown to disregard Burr’s attempts at a cooperative conversation. Ergo, this implies a tense atmosphere and distrust between the two.

tate_text:
Fighting/disagreement is a normal part of a healthy relationship. Yeezy met his girl high and now they’re having a fight.

The Drake-like self interruption (“She get under your skin if you-uh”) is also known as aposiopesis.

With Kanye’s history of un-filtered comments, not talking might be advisable. The last time Kanye spoke negatively about a former flame in public, he caused a stir, claiming he needed to take “30 showers”  after dating Amber Rose.

Jonathan Glazier’s 2013 film Under the Skin featured Scarlett Johansson; Ye has mentioned her as his “favorite white girl.”

ref_text:
You ain't never even been charged in connection with battery
 Bitch, you ain't plugged in to nothin'
tate_text:
Em claims MGK only pretends to be affiliated with criminals, since he never had any charges pressed against him.

Em incorporates wordplay on “battery” (cell/assault), “charged” (energized/accused), “connection” (electrical circuit/association) and “plugged in to” (connected/up-to-date). This echos his lines on “ShadyXV” from the homonymous Shady Records compilation album

I’m a Duracell
But I sure as hell got it backwards ‘cause y'all get jumped
And I’ll catch the battery charge

Em, on the other hand, was sentenced to a two year long probation in 2001 for carrying a concealed weapon after he pistol whipped John Guerra, whom he allegedly saw kissing his then-wife Kim outside a nightclub. He was initially charged with assault with a dangerous weapon as well, but it was dropped as a part of a plea deal. Em has elaborated on the incident on “Sing For The Moment” and “We As Americans.”

ref_text:
All wanna see me with no pot to piss in
 But niggas been excited 'bout the grave I'm diggin'
tate_text:
The idiom “without a pot to piss in” describes someone who is extremely poor or deprived.

X believes his critics hate him so much, they can’t wait to see him dead or broke. This was especially apparent after X posted a video pretending to hang himself on Instagram. Some believed he legitimately committed suicide and welcomed his death.

The line, “But niggas been excited ‘bout the grave I’m diggin’,” refers to fans of X and other viewers listening to his song “Revenge,” which X dropped earlier than the album. He is talking about the contradiction : while people are supposed to care for him, they get excited as soon as he talks about suicide.

tate_text:
Pusha can fulfill his girl’s thirst for money for heels and money to pay the bills… but I ain’t sayin' she a gold digger.



This is a reference to a woman’s claim that she needs money to pay her legitimate expenses – her bills – when the money really goes towards superfluous purchases like expensive high heels. Pusha is wise to her game and knows that she is really asking to be spoiled.

This could also be a slur of “Hill money,” a reference to Hillman College from The Cosby Show. This would tie to “Bill money” later in the line as a reference to Bill Cosby. This may seem unlikely, but Kanye has referenced Hillman before.

ref_text: So I, I am headed home
tate_text:
The theme of loss and running back to familiarity and safety (symbolised by ‘home’) is a common theme in Bon Iver lyrics and in fact is a central theme of his breakout album For Emma, Forever Ago. The idea of not being to “last these shows” is also used in the title track of the album.

(Running home, running home, running home, running home…)

In theme with “Monster”, Bon Iver wistfully sings about a time when he wasn’t caught up in the lights, a simpler, happier time.

I do know that it was a large space, because you could hear the reverb of the space in a lot of the tracks even when you didn’t want it. I think he liked the vibe there more than thinking it was a good place to make a good-sounding recording.

ref_text: I am a god
tate_text:
Kanye discusses this track during his interview with Zane Lowe for BBC Radio 1, during which he says that this song prompted reactions like: “‘I Am a God’? Who does he think he is?,” to which Kanye responds, “I just told you who I thought I was! A god! That’s who I think I am.”



He continues to ask, “Would it have been better if I had a song that said I was a ‘gangsta’? Or if I had a song that said I was a ‘pimp’? All those colors and patinas fit better on a person like me, right? But to say you are a god, especially when you got shipped over to the country you’re in, and your last name is a slave owner’s… How could you say that?”

ref_text: [Part I: Produced by Sounwave]
tate_text:
Sounwave is a member of TDE’s main production group, Digi+Phonics, who also produced “Bitch Don’t Kill My Vibe.”

The production has an amped up feel—a change of pace from the majority of the tracks on the album. Kendrick explains his harsh realities over haunting string melodies.

About halfway through the song, the beat switch channels an old-school West Coast feel—the arrival of MC Eiht, one of the great rappers of that era, furthers the effect. Eiht, like Kendrick, hails from Compton, CA, and was a part of hip-hop group Compton’s Most Wanted.
Compton is also the hometown of rap group N.W.A. of that same era (late 80s-early 90s) featuring Eazy-E, MC Ren, Dr. Dre, Ice Cube and DJ Yella.

The second part of the song is produced by Terrace Martin and samples “Don’t Change Your Love” by The Five Stairsteps. He also samples the late B.B. King’s “Chains N Things” just after he begins the second verse.

The outro features a classic West Coast G-Funk sound circa The Chronic and Doggystyle as a nod to the sound he was influenced by growing up, layering pitch shifts for a surreal effect.

ref_text:
I snuck up out the parts where niggas be living heartless
 And cannot tell the difference between Iraqi, Israeli
 And so I'm wondering really what could you actually tell me
tate_text:
Cole is highlighting the ignorance of the people back from where he came from. By saying that they cannot tell the difference between Iraq and Israel, two very different countries with completely contrasting political and cultural ideologies, despite being geographically close, he is making a comment on how some people are solely focused on themselves and uneducated about other world issues and events. Since they are that simple-minded, there is nothing that they could actually teach Cole.

This could also be a general comment about the ignorance of American foreign policy and awareness about other parts of the world as a whole.

ref_text:
Motherfuckers say that I'm foolish, I only talk about jewels (Bling bling)
 Do you fools listen to music or do you just skim through it?
tate_text:
All I know about music is that not many people ever really hear it. And even then, on the rare occasions when something opens within, and the music enters, what we mainly hear, or hear corroborated, are personal, private, vanishing evocations.

Jay-Z’s opening “Renegade” lines reflect the themes of the above, found in James Baldwin’s 1957 devastating short story, “Sonny’s Blues.”  In a situation similar to the drug-addicted “Sonny” in Baldwin’s piece, it is only through music that Jay is able to externalize his pain, confront his past, and muse on his current situation.

A topic of discussion that has been present throughout Jay’s career is how this street-smart emotional vulnerability has not always registered with, or been appreciated by, critics and listeners. Here Hov openly lambastes those in that category, suggesting that they are only superficially listening to his discography—judging it solely off tracks such as “Big Pimpin'” and “Money, Cash, Hoes;” while ignoring introspective cuts such as “Where I’m From,” “You Must Love Me” and “This Life Forever.”

In his 2010 autobiography Decoded Jay pointed out the target of these lines:

This is directed at critics who only listen to songs that fulfill their preconceived notions-the ‘bling bling’ in the background summarizes their usual complaint about my music.

Swear I wanna die, yeah, when you cross my—
 Said I wanna die, yuh, no, I'm not alright, yuh
tate_text:
X struggles mentally and is always tipping on the edge of suicide, hence the “swear I wanna die” line. However, he keeps a promise to his friends and fanbase that he would never take his own life, as stated here in the “said I wouldn’t die” line, even though he is constantly feeling pain.

Suicide is a common theme throughout X’s music, for example, the song “Jocelyn Flores” is dedicated to close friend of X’s who committed suicide in May 2017. X is among a new generation of people in the Hip-hop community known for bringing public attention to mental health, speaking about his own issues, and being a voice for others.

ref_text: One day your daddy called me, told me he had a funny feeling
tate_text:
This is the start of the verse of which is from Jermaine’s (J Cole’s) view, opposed to the rest of the song which is from his friend James McMillan Jr. who died at the age of 22. James McMillan Jr. is mentioned not only in this song but at the end of changes where Jermaine reminisced on when he found out that his friend had died.

Jermaine describes a vivid memory within this verse about his last conversation with James before he died at the age of 22, when he tells him about how he wasn’t given enough time to make his amends but praises his only daughter as his greatest accomplishment.

This line is the start of the conversation between the two on the phone, just before James opens up to Jermaine about his life and feelings.

'Cause no one oversees these cops and
 All we see is 'em beat charges
tate_text:
Em questions the accountability of the police force. Despite the presence of bodycam footage and intense media scrutiny, the number of policemen who face serious consequences for police brutality are still statistically low.

As reported by CNN:

Between 2005 and April 2017, 80 officers have been arrested on murder or manslaughter charges for on-duty shootings. During that 12-year span, 35% were convicted, while the rest were pending or not convicted.

More specifically, regarding Freddie Gray, referenced earlier in the song:

Three of the six officers involved were acquitted of all charges, including one of murder. Prosecutors also dropped all charges against three other officers, ending one of the most closely watched and unsuccessful police prosecutions in the nation. [x]

ref_text:
Kick your shoes off, let your hair down
 (And go berserk) all night long
 Grow your beard out, just weird out
 (And go berserk) all night long
tate_text:
Eminem wants you to have fun all night, and party! He loves having a good time, getting weird, and growing facial hair, apparently. What he doesn’t like is shoes on his brand new carpet.

Seeing as Rick Rubin worked on this track, it’s funny how Em states “take your shoes off” and “grow your beard out.”
This also calls to mind lines off his song “Business”:

Can’t leave rap alone, the game needs me
‘til we grow beards, get weird and disappear
Into the mountains



“Growing the beard” is also a term used to mean “defining an identity” – so named after the TV show Star Trek: The Next Generation, in which as it started to find its identity, coincidentally one of the main characters, Commander Riker, grew a beard.

This is a reference to the popular 1982 film, E.T. The Extra Terrestrial which revolves around the protagonist, Elliot’s efforts to help a stranded alien, E.T., on Earth return back to his home planet. He has the powers of levitation which allows Elliot and a band of teenagers to escape law enforcement during a bike chase.

X claims he feels as if he’s flying, similar to E.T., when he’s taking Adderall, a drug that causes euphoria and enhances cognitive function.

ref_text:
And it's ten for the wolf and
 Three for the shepherd,
tate_text:
The Wolf and the Shepherd is one of Aesop’s Fables in which a wolf followed a flock of sheep for a long time, and did not attempt to injure one of them. The Shepherd at first stood on his guard against the Wolf, as against an enemy, and kept a strict watch over his movements. But when the Wolf, day after day, kept in the company of the sheep, did not make the slightest effort to seize them, the Shepherd began to look upon him as a guardian of his flock rather than as a plotter of evil against it. When occasion called him one day into the city, he left the sheep entirely in his charge. The Wolf, now that he had the opportunity, fell upon the sheep, and destroyed the greater part of the flock. The Shepherd, on his return, finding his flock destroyed, exclaimed: “I have been rightly served; why did I trust my sheep to a Wolf?”



The “ten” for the wolf, who was cunning, is significantly more than the “three” for the shepherd, who tried to do the right thing. X is using this Aesop Fable to emphasize what the devil told him: being cunning and evil will get you what you want.

tate_text:
Ariana Grande has discussed her panic/anxiety attacks, as well as feeling dissociated due to PTSD-like symptoms. Here, she talks about how it’s difficult to bring oneself out of these situations.

There are no one-size-fit-all solutions to attacks, dissociation or many common PTSD symptoms, much less anything like medicines or herbs. However, the most common advice, generally, is to breathe.

Ariana Grande told TIME :

I never opened  up about it, because I thought that was how life was supposed to feel.

Ariana has since revealed that therapy played a big part in her recovery. A common therapy technique is also breathing therapy.

Satisfaction is the death of desire!!
You want what you can’t have. The reason Em wanted the girl so badly is because he never thought he had a chance with her, he liked the thrill of pursuing her more than the girl herself. Once he got with the girl, he reached his goal and had no feelings for her.

Eminem revisited this idea on “River” from  Revival:

And now that I got you I don’t want you
Took advantage of my thirst to pursue

Referring to Em’s other songs “25 to life” and “Almost Famous”, Em might also be talking about the rap game here. He tried so hard being the number one in the game. He tried so hard to be famous. But once he’s famous, he found it’s hard to handle it.

ref_text: And I, I wouldn't last these shows
tate_text:
This could refer to the situation that the late Michael Jackson was faced with when he announced his monster 50-date concert series at the O2 Arena at London. Most skeptics believed he wouldn’t have the energy to last that long (and unfortunately Michael passed away before he can prove the skeptics wrong or right). This can refer to Kanye’s suicidal thoughts or the times he cried on stage while singing “Hey Mama” in honor of his mother.

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KULTTPUOL98

It could also refer to Kanye not attending and participating in any more telethons or award ceremonies (the shows). He knows he’s outspoken and wouldn’t last anymore in them when everyone knows his pedigree. He’s a monster, he can’t be tamed.

Furthermore, he had to cancel his national tour with Lady Gaga as a result of Taylor-gate.

ref_text:
The
 Tears don't show, won't hurt me now 'cause
 Heart's been broke
tate_text:
X is saying he is already broken and therefore you cannot do any worse to him. The fact that he has reached such a low means that he cannot be hurt more than he already has been. He feels as if since his heart was broken, he has been completely desensitised and is numb to pain.

The fact that his “heart’s been broke” is symbolised with a tattoo of a broken heart below his left eye, and the fact he has become numb is symbolised with one below his right eye. He touches on this numb stage in his life in his “No Jumper” interview.

She experienced anxiety after the May 2017 terrorist bombing, following her performance in Manchester, United Kingdom. “My body’s here on Earth, but I’m floating,” is a psychological disorder known as depersonalization, which is when a person’s thoughts or feelings seem unreal.

This is a God dream
 This is a God dream
 This is a God dream
 
 [Chorus: Kanye West & Choir]
 We on an ultralight beam
 We on an ultralight beam
 This is a God dream
 This is a God dream
 This is everything
 Everything (Thing, thing, thing)
tate_text:
“Ultralight beam” may refer to the conversion of St. Paul on the road to Damascus, as told in Acts 9:3:

And as he journeyed, he came near Damascus: and suddenly there shined round about him a light from heaven.

Originally known as Saul of Tarsus, Paul persecuted early followers of Jesus until he was converted by God. God appeared to Saul as a “beam of light” and blinded him for 3 days. After he was converted, Saul changed his name to Paul and became one of the most important figures in early Christianity.

Kanye clarified on Twitter that the title The Life of Pablo referred to Paul and described him as “the most powerful messenger of the first century.”

A fresco painting by Michelangelo titled The Conversion of Saul is housed in the Cappella Paolina, Vatican City and depicts a “beam of light” coming down on Paul. Michelangelo is one of Kanye’s many inspirations.

ref_text: Have you ever served a fiend with a pocket full of soap?
tate_text:
Crack cocaine and soap share similarities in color and texture. “Dummy rocks” are soap shavings made to look like crack. Cole’s friend James, whose perspective he raps from for most of the album, was a dealer that sold crack to fiends, or addicts.

50 Cent rapped about passing soap off for cocaine on “Life’s On The Line”:

I’m that nigga that sold coke, the nigga that sold dope
The nigga that shot dice, went broke and sold soap

ref_text: Last week was my rough week
tate_text:
He went through a lot last week, and had a very stressful one; which leads to the better annotated next line:



This is also a key change in his life, a con of fame if you will, as, in “Rescue You”, he says

You had a long day, I can tell by your face

and then, in “Enemy”, he says

Girl, I been drinkin' all day
Its been a long week,
Can’t you tell by my face?

“Enemy” was released after House Of Balloons, Thursday and Echoes Of Silence, and since he’s had to start making music for a living, this clearly shows that the effects of fame are rubbing off on him.

On another note,

When Abel sings “ Last week was my rough week” he is referring to taking a week of pills/opiates. When you stop taking opiates you always have one tough week of withdrawing and then things get better. You still experience some symptoms after the first week, hence the  next line “ I’m still drippin' down from my nose.”

ADDITION (based on suggestion): This line also shows that Eliza is not as oblivious as initially thought. Seeing as marriages in those days typically required the couple to become closer AFTER the actual marriage (see: Hamilton asking Philip Schuyler for Eliza’s hand after two weeks of courtship), Eliza understands her position in Alexander’s life and heart. tate_text:
Kendrick alludes to the San Francisco Bay Area, but may also have the Emerald Triangle in mind (a triumvirate consisting of Mendocino, Humboldt and Trinity county). This region lies just north of San Francisco County in Northern California—both areas are renowned for their liberal majority and significant cannabis culture, stemming from the 1960s counterculture movement.



Kush (or OG Kush) refers to a cannabis indica strain popular among rappers, especially those from the West Coast. A pound of marijuana is the equivalent of about 450 grams and would typically be purchased with the intent of selling for a profit.

ref_text:
And still put hands on you
 Stayin' wound up is how I spend time (Get it?)
tate_text:
Em starts a triple entendre here with “still put hands on you”.


The last thing you’re likely to add to a snowman would be some sticks for arms then some mittens or gloves for hands.
Before, Em makes a reference to beef (ground beef). Now he will “put hands on you"— common slang term for hitting someone—but specifically, he "put[s] hands on you” in the way someone puts their hands on round chuck, when making burgers.
Watches have hands put on the face to tell the time. Hereafter, he starts a larger play on words about time.



“Stayin' wound up is how I spend time” goes with the time reference, and is also a triple entendre.


There are watches that, instead of running off of a battery, have a wind up mechanism.
“Wound up” is a common phrase meaning tense, anxious or fidgety. Em spends his time being wound up, or restless and anxious.
“Spend” is a homophone for “spin”. A watch being wound up is what makes the hands spin. In other words, the mechanism being wound up spins time.

ref_text:
Bring ya work home on top of me
 I'm-a let you be the, be the boss of me
tate_text:
A sexual innuendo. When you’re the boss you’re in control. In this case, Jay’s in control of Beyoncé. She wants Jay to release all his stress and pent-up aggression from his rough day on her sexually.



Bey is playing with themes of power dynamics here; this line is representative of that major sexual motif on this eponymous and highly personal album. Telling her man to be the “boss”, to take control and use her as his stress relief while simultaneously repurposing the word “blow” for cunnilingus and confidently demanding her own cherry tearing release powerfully juxtaposes ideas of female dominance and submissiveness, challenging preconceived notions of feminism by choosing to not be the boss in this moment and yet easily remaining the one with the real power.

tate_text:
La palabra “chupa” en esta línea puede ser mal interpretada como “tomar alcohol”, este no es el caso en esta ocasión si tienes en cuenta las otras líneas de este verso.




This line means:

“When she sucks she really gets crazy”

but it can be misinterpreted as

“When she drinks she really gets crazy”

“Chupa” means “suck” but in some countries it’s used as “drinking alcohol”, but if you take into account the nature of the other lines in this verse the first translation is more fitting.

ref_text:
By the time you hear the next pop
 The funk shall be within you—*Gunshot*
tate_text:
Kendrick doesn’t let his enemy kill the vibe. Just like a bullet breaking the sound barrier, Kendrick is hitting us with the funk before we even recognize it. We are feeling the music before we hear the sound. It is already inside us as a society, he is just making us realize it.

This is reminiscent of Parliament’s “Bop Gun.”

Where did you get that funk from?
They’re spoiling the fun
Shoot them with the bop gun

As stated in his interview with Rolling Stone, the album ended up with a predominately funky/jazzy vibe:

Musically, the album… is adventurous, borrowing from free jazz & 1970s funk. Lamar says he listened to a lot of Miles Davis and Parliament… MixedByAli says Lamar works synesthetically – “He talks in colors all the time: ‘Make it sound purple.’ ‘Make it sound light green.’”

Kendrick’s line here is similar to Hittman on “Light Speed”, and uses a voice very similar to the narrator of Section.80.

Interestingly, Kendrick begins his rewind on Duckworth with this same POP.

ref_text: Pussy, power, profit and headache
tate_text:
Kendrick references gold diggers, who use sex to manipulate and get rich.

The Weeknd tackles the problems of achieving great wealth on Starboy, noting the disturbing elements of his newfound fame. In a Beats 1 interview, he mentioned how “Starboy” had an influence on Kendrick’s verse:

I played him songs, the “Starboy” theme, of course, which he incorporated in his verse.

The alliteration here is reminiscent of a line that 2Pac used on Me Against the World, an album which Kendrick has cited as one his 25 favorite albums of all time.

Furthermore, the run of plosive P’s recalls lines from Kendrick’s prior songs “Bitch, Don’t Kill my Vibe” and “The Jig Is Up (Dump'n)”.

ref_text: The wheels fell off, I rode the hubcap
tate_text:
“Ride until the wheels fall off,” is an expression meaning to make the most out of any situation. The idea originates from a person who’s willing to drive a car with bad tires, bad engine and on the brink of falling apart, but still determined to get to his destination.

A “hubcap” is a decorative disk that covers the centerpiece of a wheel, making the whole wheel in itself more visually appealing.



Cars cannot ride on hubcaps since they serve no real mechanical purpose. Tunechi is so determined to succeed that he’s willing to do the extreme.

tate_text:
JAY-Z plays with the imagery of having an angel on your right shoulder and the devil on your left. “Let go your ego” is a play on the popular breakfast waffle brand Eggo’s slogan “L'eggo my eggo.”

In 2014, JAY-Z and Solange Knowles (Beyoncé’s sister), were involved in an altercation in an elevator at the Met Gala. Rumors swirled that the fight had something to do with Jay’s infidelity, but neither party addressed it at the time. Here, Jay makes a play on “egg” to not only fit in the with the breakfast theme but also suggest he was responsible for instigating the conflict in the first place.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_EMZoNHOJUo

This is also a nod to a lyric Jay spit on “Public Service Announcement” from 2003’s The Black Album:

My homey Strick told me, ‘Dude finish your breakfast’

There’s also some wordplay—intentional or not—between ego, Eggos, and egged.

tate_text:
The use of “Moonlight” may refer back to X’s dark mind and past. With the release of the 2017 Freshman Cypher and his controversially satanic verse, X has since been seen as the dark figure in rap. In an April 21, 2017 interview on the Complex talk show, Everyday Struggle, Joe Budden called X the Antichrist of the new rap age. Furthermore, X continues to stand as the face of depression and mental health in music, as well as suicide. X has also dealt with many jail sentences and criticism for his relationship with Geneva Ayala, his former girlfriend who he allegedly abused. Despite all the dark connotations attached to him, X feels as though he is still able to shine.

The terms “spotlight” and “moonlight” may also be direct allusions to the attention X has been receiving from the music community and media. It seems as though he is predicting the success of the album ?, as his recent single “SAD!” released before the album debuted at number 17 on Billboard Hot 100. In an 2017 interview, he outlined his aspirations for his future as an artist:

They’re already saying I’m the most controversial artist of 2017 but nobody’s seen the half of it. I finally have everything in my fucking hands so now you’re gonna see who’s the greatest artist of the century. I’m not talking about best artist in my city, or in my country—I’m going for best artist in the world.

ref_text:
Don't make me pull the toys out, huh
 Don't make me pull the toys
 And fire up the engines, huh
 And then they make noise
tate_text:
Continuing the theme of the verses, the first 3 lines have Kanye’s rich life on full display with an onomatopoeia of an engine sound to emphasize his car collection. However, he finally echoes the weeps from the hook and the other side of fame promised in the intro, as the closing line turns around everything previously said in the song. The confident braggadocio tone in Kanye’s voice is replaced by a mourning cry, announcing the rest of the album as a display of the sad part of the story, picking up where he left off on his previous LP’s closing track:

I turn on the TV, and see me, and see nothing
What does it feel like, to live real life, to be real
Not some facade on TV that no one can really feel

Of course, the more honest side of Kanye always manages to connect with the audience better.

In the Runaway movie, he’s driving a sports car during the segment this song is playing in. Interestingly, the car crashes as Kanye delivers the last line.

Referring to his cards as “toys” is another example of Kanye’s inner child as referenced in “Through the Wire”:

I still won’t grow up, I’m a grown ass kid

ref_text: Y'all must want to start a revolution
tate_text:
Speaking to all of his critics, Jay is saying that they are overreacting so much to his visit that they might as well start a revolution to get what they want, and through the context of the song he is comparing that little revolution to the Cuban Revolution.



The first line also echoes Revolution 1 especially with the “you know” starting the second line.  http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KrkwgTBrW78

tate_text:
Venom is an extraterrestrial symbiote that can enter any host, use telepathic abilities to communicate with its host, and grant superhuman strength. It feeds off the adrenaline of its host. The symbiote also has a mind of its own and can take full control of the host at any point.

Eminem’s choppy and unpredictable flow may allude to the strange and erratic movement, expansion, and shapeshifting of the symbiote. The symbiote in its raw independent form is amorphous, which translates to its hosts when it enters them.

ref_text: [Hook: Justin Vernon & Teyana Taylor]
tate_text:
Currently an act signed to G.O.O.D. Music, at the time Teyana was Pharrell’s protege, and just a “fashion friend” of Kanye’s. She went in-depth with Complex on the making of the track:

Even though the invite really was to check out clothes, I had told myself I was going to get on that album—whether he knew or not. [Laughs.] I’m not even a morning person and he wanted me to come at 9 a.m. I get there and I like his clothes. He’s like, “I knew you’d like this!” Then he started playing his album and I start humming and doing some little runs to what I’m hearing on the sly tip. I came in there humming! I knew what I was doing. [Laughs.] So he hears me and is like, “You can really sing. Yo, can you put some backgrounds on this song ‘Hell of a Life’?” He knew I was signed to Pharrell and all that, but I guess he didn’t know what I could really do. Like I said, we were more fashion friends. He just knew I was fly. So then he tells me to do “Dark Fantasy.” At the time it was pretty empty, just verses. He put me in another room by myself and said, “Go.” I came back with a whole intro and chorus. I did all the scratches and the cuts myself with my voice. That’s not a DJ thing when you hear my voice go like that. I was so nervous when I played it for Kanye. I hadn’t been in the studio for so long. I was so excited to be trying out for that song.

ref_text: And I swear too much on the regular
tate_text:
After pointing out that he has had insane amounts of success in spite of the prevalence and mainstream preference for “blue-eyed soul” when it comes to things like radio play, Abel cites two reasons why he is cast out in the following lines.

First, he points to his image: his signature disheveled look and his drug-filled lifestyle that filled his trilogy of mixtapes and has remained a staple of his music ever since. Secondly, Abel points to his frequent profanity as a reason why he does not get as much exposure from traditional music outlets, which tend to favor “radio-friendly” content with minimal profanity.

ref_text:
I don't really go outside 'cause I hate traffic
 I don't wanna go outside, get caught in traffic, traffic
tate_text:
“Traffic” symbolizes reality—going out and facing reality rather than staying stuck inside your own mind. Just like traffic, the truth can be chaotic and frustrating, but it’s necessary to weather it if you want to get where you’re going.
X could also be dreading the meaningless interaction that comes with being surrounded by other people that are constantly making small talk, or a reference to social anxiety.

The second line also suggests that he fears being confronted by any opposition (contemporary rappers, etc) while outside – getting “caught.”

ref_text:
I can hold my liquor
 But this man can’t handle his weed
tate_text:
When Vernon says “this man can’t handle his weed”, “this man” that he is talking about is actually Chief Keef and his version of the hook. Vernon’s hook is blurry and distorted, so it is trying to represent the effects of alcohol. And Chief Keef’s hook is displaying the effects of weed, as you can actually hear Chief Keef inhaling and exhaling smoke right before he starts his hook. Since both versions come from Kanye’s point of view, this “argument” demonstrates his inner turmoil. There’s a side of Kanye that is over-the-top cocky, but also a “dark and lonely” side that makes him feel worthless.

These two hooks are Kanye’s version of a devil and an angel on his shoulders fighting for control, since the messages both contradict themselves. Vernon’s hook shows Kanye trying to convince himself that he is awesome, even though he knows deep down that he’s just a lonely loser. And Chief Keef’s hook is Kanye beating himself up, even though in this version he thinks that deep down he is awesome and god-like.

tate_text:
Drake’s perspective on “picking up the pieces” has changed over the years. On “Connect,” a song from Drake’s 2013 album Nothing Was The Same, he sang:

But when it falls apart, I’m always still down
To pick a million tiny little pieces off the ground
Wish you would learn to love people and use things
And not the other way around

At that time, Drake seemed willing to put effort into fixing his relationships. More recently, on his 2016 track “Redemption” from Views, he expressed his frustration about the same kind of situation:

Why do I settle for women that force me to pick up the pieces?

It’s clear that he’s grown tired of trying to fix his dysfunctional relationships.

ref_text: Don't mind, all my writings on the wall
tate_text:
On the surface, this could refer to walls written with miscellaneous things. Interestingly enough, this is how cavemen communicated early in human history, presenting a potentially visceral characterization of The Weeknd.

The “writings on the wall” is also idiomatic. As an idiom, Abel is alluding to his warnings to girls not to fall in love with him. His lifestyle is so obvious, or stands out as much as writing would on a wall, but girls still keep falling in love with him.

Tumblr has many pictures of his lyrics written on walls or spray painted places.

ref_text:
Always worried 'bout the critics who ain't ever fuckin' did it
 I write what's in my heart, don't give a fuck who fuckin' with it
 But in a sense I can relate, the need to be great
 Turns into an obsession and keeps a nigga up late
 Writin' words, hopin' people observe the dedication
 That stirs in you constantly, but intentions get blurred
tate_text:
As Cole discusses in Eyez, success is never guaranteed, so while he’s still on top, Cole will speak from his heart until he’s not at his peak.



At this point in his career, Cole isn’t following the rules that the music industry sets for upcoming artists. 2014 Forest Hills Drive had no radio songs and little promotion. In an interview with Sway, Cole spoke about building his fan base instead of creating a target audience.

I literally had to come to grips that this album might not sell, because we’re not doing this traditionally. And I didn’t have no singles, nobody heard any music. It was a scary thing for me, but I believed even if it don’t sell and ya’ll like it—cool. It didn’t sell? I came to terms with that already.

In previous lines, Cole spoke on his friend who wants to be famous and respected. While Cole not only achieved that, he placed his importance on other things such as family and music. However, Cole can still relate because that’s all he wanted in his early career.

tate_text:
Lin Manuel-Miranda often sings praises for Aaron Sorkin’s show, The West Wing. The phrase “room where it happened/happens” is used periodically throughout the show to represent exactly what is being represented in this song. In the show, Sam Seaborn, played by Rob Lowe, refers to the Oval Office as ‘the room where it happens’ in episode 20 Hours in America. The phrase is even the name of the 8th episode in season 6.

This is only one of the myriad of West Wing references in Hamilton – my favorite of which is Sam Seaborn saying “because before I look at anything I look for a mind at work” to Ainsley Hayes.

ref_text: The conversation lasted two minutes
tate_text:
…and yet in that short time, she completely fell for him.

This obviously isn’t Angelica being shallow since, well, it’s Angelica. It seems more likely to be a reinforcement of just how intelligent and witty Hamilton is, that in two minutes, maybe three minutes he can woo someone as hard to impress as Angelica, as well as proving what Burr said about him earlier about him being “reliable with the ladies”.

Perhaps that earlier moment during “A Winter’s Ball” was to set up Hamilton’s flirting skills in order for this to make sense, since before then we hadn’t seen him flirt with anyone besides Laurens possibly…okay, probably.

ref_text: Now I'm the bad guy, call me Chun-Li (ooh)
tate_text:
Nicki expresses the fact that she could be seen as a “bad guy” for ruining her unfaithful boyfriend’s reputation after exposing him as a cheater. “Chun-Li” was the lead single of Nicki’s 2018 album, Queen, named after a character from the Street Fighter video game franchise. This also incorporates a line from a spoken interlude on Nicki’s track. which takes inspiration from a monologue in Scarface:

Oh, I get it, huh, they paintin' me out to be the bad guy
Well it’s the last time you gonna see a bad guy do the rap game like me

Like how Chun-Li was the first female character in Street Fighter, Nicki has been able to lay the grounds for the female rap scene, and remains one of the most influential women in the genre today.

Before referencing the character on her own song, she mentioned her in her feature on Willow Smith’s “Fireball.”

I breathe on the mirror, I don't see my breath
 Possibly I'm dead, I must be possessed
 Like an evil spell, I'm E-V-I-L (Evil, spelled)
tate_text:
Before modern medicine, physicians would hold mirrors to the human mouth and look for fog to determine if a person was still breathing.



The “Evil, spelled” adlib was added in post-production as a subtle jab towards critics who failed to notice some of the complex rhyme schemes from his 2017 album, Revival. Eminem addresses critics directly later in this track. The adlib itself rhymes with “evil spell” and notes that he spelt out evil – E-V-I-L.

Earlier on this track, Em spoon fed listeners a pun in a similar fashion:

Maybe “Stan” just isn’t your cup of tea (get it)

ref_text: Ooh, that pussy good, won't you sit it on my taste bloods?
tate_text:
Kendrick conflates “bloods” with “buds” so that both words are heard. He mentioned his “taste bloods” previously in the God Is Gangsta extended music video—there is a frame that displays the words:



“Taste blood” is an idiom used to indicate something exciting—oral sex, in Kendrick’s case. He may also be alluding to the Blood gang.

ref_text: Alexander, come back to sleep
tate_text:
Historical buzzkill time: Alexander actually wrote the letter quoted here on July 4th, about a week before the duel. And he spent the night the duel at his pied-à-terre downtown while Eliza was uptown at home. The Broadway show compresses the timeline for simplicity and dramatic effect.

Hamilton’s son and first biographer wrote this account of that final night:

[Hamilton] entered the room, gazed pensively at the boy, and asked if he would share his bed that night. Hamilton “soon retired, and placing [the boy’s] little hands on his own, he repeated with him the Lord’s Prayer.” The child then fell asleep in his arms. This image of Hamilton sleeping with his arms wrapped around an orphaned youth during his last night on earth is inexpressibly poignant and makes one think that his own tormented boyhood weighed on his mind that night.

ref_text: Raise a glass to freedom
tate_text:
This is a line that is repeated from “The Story Of Tonight” which has an ironic meaning here. Hamilton was the last of the four friends to get married. Hercules Mulligan got married in 1773. Lafayette followed in 1774. John Laurens married second last in 1776.

The friends used this line to describe the freedom of America in the aformentioned song. This time, they are joking around, because they are at a wedding, and they are saying that they don’t have freedom anymore. They joke that they lost their freedom because of their wives, which is confirmed in the second next line, “Something you will never see again.”

ref_text:
Started from the bottom like a snowman
 Oh man, put that in your corncob pipe and smoke that
tate_text:
Em restates the line that he used to start off the song, comparing himself to a snowman, only to take a different stab at it.

As a stand-alone line, “started from the bottom like a snowman” is a corny thing to rap (let alone to start off a song with). But Em is clearly aware of this and confidently recalls attention to the opening verse — which was actually a very clever set of bars building from “ground up” like a snowman to eventually “way in the sky“.

He is taunting his detractors who would dismiss the line as corny by furthering the snowman reference (snowmen are often decorated with a pipe), saying “put that in your corncob pipe and smoke that”, basically meaning “fuck you”, and if you didn’t catch the meaning, smoke some weed and maybe that will help.

A “corncob pipe” is a regular pipe, only replaced by a corn on the cob. This might be an allusion to Frosty The Snowman. In the popular Christmas song, Frosty is depicted like this:

Frosty the Snowman
Was a jolly happy soul
With a corncob pipe and a button nose
And two eyes made out of coal

ref_text:
Cause all I see are wings, I can see your wings
 But I know what I am and the life I live, yeah, the life I live
 And even though I sin, maybe we are born to live
 But I know time will tell if we're meant for this
 Yeah, if we're meant for this
tate_text:
The biblical terms “sin” and “angel” represent the difference between Abel and the girls he preys on.

Similar to the line in his version of “Odd Look” in which he sings:

All you girls try to be saints, I’ll make you roll with a sinner.

Abel is a clear-cut sinner, his lifestyle consisting primarily of drugs and sex. This girl represents purity, being untouched by his “madness” initially. The two are polar opposites and will co-exsist regardless of how well they get along. This is truly the beauty behind the madness.

Abel has been this character since the beginning and he convinces ordinary girls to fall for him so he can can “live life for the moment.” This leads to a constant cycle of give and take, as these “angels” are willing to give Abel everything they can while he only takes from them. He wonders if the two can live this way, and if so, for how long.

This could also be interpreted as being about his rise to fame – he loves his old time fans, but now he’s hoping that he can truly “live” and come into his own in the mainstream. He hopes this transition will be successful, but only time will tell if someone like him is meant for this.

ref_text: Damned if I do, if I don't (Yuh)
tate_text:
This line may allude to John Calvin’s theory of predestination, which states that your fate is decided long before you are born—that you are destined for either Heaven or Hell regardless of your actions during life.

Kendrick Lamar touches on many religious concepts on DAMN.. On “FEAR.,” Lamar receives a voicemail from his cousin Carl Duckworth. In the voicemail, Carl Duckworth says the following:

But you have to understand this, man, that we are a cursed people Deuteronomy 28:28 says, ‘The Lord shall smite thee with madness And blindness, and astonishment of heart’
See, family, that’s why you feel like you feel
Like you got a chip on your shoulder

Kendrick Lamar seems to be applying a similar philosophy in this line. He believes that he is damned to Hell no matter what he does in life.

This line also concerns Lamar’s perceived popularity in the music industry. Though he has achieved major success, he is still a controversial figure. Kendrick Lamar’s 2015 release, To Pimp a Butterfly, touched on topics such as racism and police brutality in songs like “Alright.” Throughout DAMN., Lamar plays a clip from Fox News of two reporters speaking about the song. Here’s what they had to say:

Lamar stated his views on police brutality
With that line in the song, quote:
‘And we hate the popo, wanna kill us in the street fo’ sho'.‘
Oh please, ugh, I don’t like it

Here, Lamar demonstrates awareness of the fact that whether or not he releases a great album, he will be heavily criticized by experts and casual listeners alike.

ref_text: I'll prolly die because I ain't know Demarcus was snitchin'
tate_text:
The use of the names “Demarcus,” “Marcus,” or “Mark” in this circumstance is not new, however Kendrick displays the connotation subtly within the context of “FEAR.”  Kendrick is implying that Demarcus, his “mark” (or target), rolled on him. This, in turn, exposed some sort of illegal activity on Kendrick’s part.

The connotation between the two words was additionally used in a verse from the 1996 track “Murder”, performed by Bun B of UGK.

Calling a person a “mark” was a very common insult some years ago, usually referencing a person being cheated in some way. The term originates from the rise of Confidence Tricks used by con artists in the mid 1800’s, where targets of the scams were referred to as “marks.”

 Sing for the laughter and sing for the tear (Come on!)
 Sing it with me, it's just for today
 Maybe tomorrow the good Lord will take you away
tate_text:
In a song that deals with the impact of music on the listeners, this chorus, sampled directly from Aerosmith’s iconic 1973 power ballad “Dream On”, deals with its impact on the artists.

Life is short, so even artists like Eminem that are reluctant to embrace their impact on listeners eventually feel the need to “sing for the moment” and create music with real meaning while you still have the chance. Em later turned this concept into an Academy Award-winning single with “Lose Yourself”.

 Ain't no nigga that she holding

tate_text:
Her love isn’t for any man; It’s for the money. Hence, her love is “foreign”; no one can understand it, as only those in her precise position would. Money and the utility she derives from it have her heart more than anything else.

She’s also not used to receiving emotions associated with “real love.” She gets the rawest form of lust or “fake love” from guys that just want the one-nighter, which distorts her idea of what “love” really is.

Ultimately, her chosen lifestyle will leave her alone, and the only thing she’ll be holding is that pole.

ref_text: I'm hangin' on a hangover
tate_text:
The hangover for Ye is the lingering pain of the end of his relationship with Alexis Phifer five years ago. She was his intoxication, and now Ye is dealing with the headaches and feverish desire of an alcoholic because of her.

ref_text:
Raise a glass to freedom
 Something they can never take away
tate_text:
Many of the Founding Fathers were obsessed with legacies, success or other measurable things. Laurens advocated for the end of slavery; Hamilton wanted to be remembered; Lafayette and Mulligan were both determined to free America from British rule.
None of these goals were guaranteed; they all involved taking risks with the hopes of succeeding. However, freedom is something that, in the minds of these men, they are fighting for something that is undeniable. Freedom is so entirely fundamental, that even if they do not have their other dreams, freedom is something that they can rely on so when they raise their glasses to freedom, they are raising their glasses to their only guarantee. These men don’t know if they will live or die; they don’t know if they’ll be remembered or just be another name in history. All that they do know is that they are free and that they will die free. This is something that they fall back on; with everything else unknown and doubtable, they need some sort of guarantee to keep themselves safe and their freedom is this guarantee.

ref_text: [Produced by  Noah "40" Shebib and Hagler/Co-Produced by Jake One]
tate_text:
Jake One is the main producer on this track. He did the body of the work while 40 mixed and mastered it, and One thought it was a nice addition to it. One did a short “interview” of sorts on the making of the track and it’s sampling issues.

The jazzy, soulful beat is driven by it’s drums and piano cords. Drake brings it together to make this track, and the laid back vibe makes it’s easy to jam to. You can hear the piano drive it along with various other  effects and hits to make it a little more modern.

Jake One is credited using his “old school ways” on why he doesn’t tell where anything is sampled from, but that’s where the choir part is from, (until 40 had a live one done in Toronto). Gene Brown originally found that sample, and he has worked to find samples with a number of countless producers. Jake had talked and sent beats to Drake for years, but Drake finally said listening to it, “This is the one”.

There was just something about the dynamic of that band, in that church

Due to sampling issues, the track was then sent to G Koop who remade the parts with issues that night and resent it that morning. Then 40 added the finishing touches to bring it together.

ref_text: Then skate with your bitch like we Tonya Harding
tate_text:
Tonya Harding is a US figure skater known for her involvement in the attack on fellow skater, Nancy Kerrigan.



Tonya Harding



Nancy Kerrigan

Jeff Gillooly, Harding’s ex husband, and Shawn Eckhart, Harding’s former body guard, conspired against Kerrigan so that she would not be able to compete in the 1994 Winter Olympics. They hired Shane Stant to break Kerrigan’s leg. Kerrigan only received a bruise from the attack, however they succeeded as she had to withdraw from the 1994 Olympics.

Harding withdrew from the 1994 Olympics and pled guilty in court, “escaping” jail time. However her co-conspirators weren’t so lucky. Later, the US Figure Skating Association stripped Harding of the title from the 1994 US Figure Skating Championship.

ref_text: When I touch down, I'ma shake shit up
tate_text:
Let’s face it: no artist is quite like The Weeknd. His singing style is certainly unique and he has a voice that you could recognize anywhere. You better believe that he knows what he is talking about.

In addition, as the singer claims that he “touches down”, he is playing off of the previous lyric (“from the ground”), since things that are fly (get it?) eventually “touch down”. He also mentioned “another world” in a previous lyric. He also goes on to mention Apollo.

In addition, “touch down” could be a play on the word “touchdown” which is a common football term. He did mention “floor seats” before and could be some subtle wordplay.

ref_text: Death over dishonor
tate_text:
A common saying where a man would rather die than to bring shame or disgrace upon himself.



This was an often repeated theme for 2Pac’s music, including “Troublesome”, “If I Fail”, and “Life of an Outlaw”.





In contrast to the message of glory and honor for a college-educated rapper like J. Cole, “death before dishonor” is also a common expression among United State Marine Corps members and alumni.

ref_text:
Tiptoein' around my name, nigga, you lame
 And when I get at you, homie
 Don't you just tell me you was just playin'
 Oh, I was just playin', K-Dot
 C'mon, you know a nigga rock with you, bro
tate_text:
This could be a shot at Drake, who’s been involved in a subliminal war with Kendrick since 2013’s “Control.”

Kendrick mentioned Drake’s name on “Control,” but Drake has never put Kendrick’s name in a verse. However, he has subbed him on numerous occasions, including “The Language,” “Shit (Remix),” “6PM in New York,” “Used To,” “100,” and “Summer Sixteen.” The irony of these bars is the receiver is left unnamed, likely to leave the general public to decide.

In 2016, Drake tiptoed around Kendrick’s name again on “For Free:”

And like your boy from Compton said
You know this dick ain’t free!

Big Sean, another possible target of these lines who also has a history of possibly sending subliminal shots at Kendrick, might have tiptoed around Dot’s name in his 2016 song “No More Interviews.”

Sean mentioned “the savior of rap"—something Kendrick essentially refers to himself as on the same song.

These lines draw similarities to 21 Savage’s “No Heart.”

ref_text: You don't know what the fuck I've been through
tate_text:
Given that 8 Mile was largely based on Eminem’s life, his character Jimmy/B-Rabbit and him share many of the same struggles that Eminem actually faced while growing up in Detroit.
In the movie, B-Rabbit’s mom is a broke alcoholic who lives in a trailer with an abusive boyfriend and her daughter. Just as Eminem is protective of his daughter Hailie, Jimmy is protective of his little sister, which leads to several arguments with his mom regarding her irresponsibility as a parent.
In addition to trying to escape a broken home and poverty, Jimmy struggles greatly as a white artist trying to succeed in a predominantly black art form, reflecting Eminem’s own problems with being booed off stage during similar rap battles. With all of this pent-up rage and suffering, Jimmy angrily lashes out at Papa Doc, claiming someone as entitled as him (as Jimmy explains following these lines) could never understand the pressure and problems that Jimmy faces.

Yeah
 Ten toes to the ground
 Yeah
tate_text:
“Ten toes to the ground” simply means to be 100% committed to something. It’s a likely reference to Kendrick’s line in “Complexion (A Zulu Love)”. Kendrick’s original phrase “ten toes down” echoes the same theme of commitment, particularly in reference to a liberation cause.  Cole cleverly merges “ten toes down” with “down to the ground” by removing the common keyword  “down” which only amplifies his dedication.

We can imagine the conversation between Lamar & Cole going something like this:

Kendrick: “I’m ready to kill these other rappers. You ten toes down?”

Cole: “Yeah homie! I’m ten toes to the ground.”

You talking money, need a hearing aid
 You talking bout me, I don't see the shade
 Switch up my style, I take any lane
 I switch up my cup, I kill any pain
tate_text:
Abel made over $55 million in 2016 after the release of his highly successful 2015 album, Beauty Behind The Madness, so he doesn’t care about anyone else’s wealth or what they say about him; he’s made it on his own.

“Starboy” is a huge musical change from Beauty Behind the Madness, and that album was a large change from both Trilogy and Kiss Land. Even when Abel changes styles, he stays on top. Should people talk bad about him because of this new style change, throwing shade, they won’t make it close enough for him to hear it so he remains oblivious to all criticism.

Finally, Abel’s never been one to hide his love of drugs that he’ll indulge in to numb his pain. This song isn’t the first time he’s poured up. He’s said before, “Bring the cups, baby, I could bring the drank.”

ref_text: [GEORGE]
tate_text:
A little history lesson on George Eacker:

When Phillip went to the theatre to challenge him to a duel, he was accompanied by Richard Price, a close friend of Phillip Hamilton. Eacker took part in two duels, the first with Price on November 22, 1801, where both fired their weapons and missed. In that scenario, both men maintain their honour and move on.

Eacker’s duel with Phillip Hamilton was just a day later (November 23), in which Eacker killed his opponent.

Just under 3 years later, Eacker died of tuberculosis on January 4, 1804.

ref_text:
Now you scramblin' and hopin' to get hot again
 But you forgot you only popped 'cause you was ridin' trends
 Now you old news and you goin' through regrets
tate_text:
Seems like Cole stays taking notes from the boss. This same topic was recently breached by JAY-Z after the release of his 4:44 album. He sat down with Dean Baquet, the executive editor of the New York Times, in an interview to discuss race, politics and the music industry. Hov spoke this wisdom when asked about ridin trends and being hot again:


BAQUET But will you have the same adventures in your life? Will you have the same stuff to write about? Or maybe you don’t know.

JAY-Z I think that rap in particular is a young man’s sport, that I’ll move out of that white-hot space. Rap is about the gift of discovery. The white-hot space is when it’s fresh and new, and it’s like, this is the hottest song ever. I mean I pushed the window, like —

BAQUET You still — you think you’re still in that space?

JAY-Z I stretched it. Oh, I stood in that window a really long time. But still, no, I don’t think people are looking to me as like, The Thing.

BAQUET Is that hard to deal with, or did you feel like, I’m O.K. with that, because I’ve moved on?

JAY-Z No.

BAQUET You don’t want to be.

JAY-Z ‘Cause I, at the end of the day we gonna find out it’s not about the white-hot space, but it’s about finding the truth. That white-hot space — people think it’s the biggest thing, but it’s really small. It’s almost like a trend.

Would you rather be a trend, or you rather be Ralph Lauren? You know what I mean; like, you rather be a trend, or you rather be forever?

I’m the person that looked at the Mona Lisa and be like, Man, that’s gonna be cool in 40 years. I play forever. And so my whole thing is to identify with the truth. Not to be the youngest, hottest, new, trendy thing.

In April of 2017, it was rumored that PnB was going to be featured in a longer version of “I Don’t Wanna do this Anymore.”

ref_text: Teamed up with the CCA
tate_text:
Today, there are more African-American adults under correctional control than were enslaved in 1850, before the Civil War.

The explosion in the size of our prison population over the last 40 years rakes in billions of dollars a year for CCA and other for-profit prison companies. The United States has built up the highest incarceration rate of any country in the world, with over 2.3 million men and women living behind bars. This is a historical anomaly; despite relatively stable incarceration rates earlier in the twentieth century, our prison population grew by 700% between 1970 and 2005, far outpacing both crime and general population growth.

And this overincarceration epidemic has a massive and disproportionate impact on people of color. If current trends continue, 1 in 3 Black men born today can expect to serve time behind bars.

More about Kanye’s CCA lyric is here: http://www.aclu.org/blog/prisoners-rights-racial-justice/kanye-west-new-slaves-and-long-tradition-locking-people-profit

And you can read all about the growth and shameful practices of CCA and other private prison companies in Banking on Bondage, our report, here: http://www.aclu.org/prisoners-rights/banking-bondage-private-prisons-and-mass-incarceration

ref_text: [Produced by Sounwave]
tate_text:
This song’s producer, Sounwave, speaks on how the record and beat came to be:

Me and Kendrick found this crazy record from this foreign group and we didn’t know where to go with it. So we looped that, I took it to my spot, and did the drums. I added everything I needed, the extra guitars, strings, all that. That inspired Kendrick to bring it to another level. Kendrick is hands-on with [beats]. He will find something he likes and call me right up: ‘Yo let’s go check this out!’

The only sample used in the song is from the Boom Clap Bachelors' “Tiden Flyver.” The sample is at the beginning of the track in the sample and in Kendrick song:

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A7vFHT9HARY#t=13

Fun Fact: Producer Robin Hannibal left Boom Clap Bachelors and formed the duo Quadron, with singer Coco O. Kendrick guests on the song “Better Off,” from Quadron’s album Avalanche.

Wayne saying he’ll walk up in the world means he has the attention of the world on him, but since it’s dark, he will surprise the world whenever he chooses to strike because it wouldn’t have seen it coming and therefore will be thoroughly surprised.

Don’t get too cocky my boy. No matter how good you are don’t ever let them see you coming. That’s the gaffe my friend. You gotta keep yourself small. Innocuous. Be the little guy. You know, the nerd… the leper… shit-kickin' surfer. Look at me.

Cole contrasts his exploration of infidelity with the fact that he is lucky to be with the woman in his life.

It was revealed in a January 2016 interview with Black Panther director Ryan Coogler that Cole is married. His wife, Melissa Heholt, has an M.S in Childhood Education and she even acts as the executive director of the Dreamville Foundation.



The double-entendre of “all over” and “I love her” strengthens Cole’s point about appreciating that he has his wife in his life.

Drake’s interest helping his romantic interests—like helping his girl realize her full potential—comes up a lot in his work. ref_text: My lonely ear pressed against the walls of your world
tate_text:
Beyoncé is alone, trying to understand what is happening in their relationship and in “his world.” He’s walled off both the world that he exists in beyond their marriage and his inner world of private thoughts. She suspects her husband is cheating but she can’t prove it. She is left hoping to “hear” what her gut has been telling her.

If interpreted literally, she may be eavesdropping on Jay in another room. The separation between them makes it seem as if they are in different worlds.

ref_text:
Unfollow fear and just say "You are blocked"
 (You can feel it, feel it, yuh)
 Just know there is so much room at the top
tate_text:
This clever lyric is not only an empowering reminder to banish fear, it also perfectly nods to the role of social media in her career.

She’s saying to “unfollow” fear and tell it that it’s been “blocked” as can be done on Twitter and Instagram. These are familiar and intuitive concepts for her fans, and somehow turns the dark, nebulous concept of fear into a manageable construct that can be willed away with the push of a button.

ref_text: I could run circles around you so fast your fuckin' head'll spin, dog
tate_text:
Eminem often plays on his pronunciation of words to create hidden meanings (or subliminal shots).

Here he says he’ll spin around you so fast your head will spin because of his superior speed, but he pronounces the word “dog”, synonym for “homie” or “man”, like the word dough.

That way, this line can also be interpreted as he will spin you so fast he’ll be making dough (soft and defenceless) out of your head, also tying in lexically with the next line about splitting different food items that refer to body parts and money.

Edit: A doughnut is also a ROUND object.

Cole expresses how in the era of Instagram and the digital age, we can become obsessed with someone attractive without knowing anything about them. He expressed feelings of possessiveness and longing that are evoked from as little as a single photograph. One of the acronyms for KOD is Kids On Drugs, in this instance referring to social media.

Cole (realcoleworld on Instagram) is notoriously quiet on social media.

ref_text: O.J. like, "I'm not black, I'm O.J." …okay
tate_text:
While on trial, O.J. Simpson supposedly uttered the quote “I’m not black, I’m O.J.” Though there’s no substantial evidence, friends and acquaintances back up the theory, and it has been used in media retelling the story since—the earliest being the 2002 documentary O.J.: A Study in Black and White. It also appeared in the 2016 documentary O.J.: Made in America as well as FX’s The People v. O.J. Simpson:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xvDMetl7mKU

JAY-Z spoke on this subject in the footnotes special for this song, noting the need for those with visibility to not cast aside their background as a scapegoat:

We tend to, as black people—‘cause we never had anything, which is understandable—we get to a place and we just think we separate ourself from the culture. You know, like where O.J. will get to a space where he’s like, “I’m not black, I’m O.J.” … It’s gonna take for the way-showers to do it and then not get to that point and then turn into like, “I ain’t black, I’m O.J.”

Other sources indicate O.J. may have said the quote during a boycott of the 1968 Olympics, when he was “reportedly pressured by his friend to ‘take a stand’ along with other black Olympic athletes.”

ref_text:
Feel my blood runnin', swear the sky's fallin'
 I know that all this shit's fabricated
tate_text:
Ariana experienced Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder (PTSD) and depersonalization after the Manchester bombing. She also suffered from anxiety for a long time before that.

She details some of the symptoms she experiences as a result of this mental issues.

Anxiety triggers a fight or flight response in her body, causing her blood pressure to spike temporarily.

The sky falling seems to detail depersonalization, a disorder described as feeling disconnected or detached from one’s body and thoughts. She feels like she’s witnessing everything in an out-of-body experience.

It also linked to the general feelings which come with anxiety – where a feeling of impending doom is a common system. She feels the sky falling due to her heightened sense of fear as a result of anxiety. She realizes however the events she fears aren’t actually occurring, but rather a fabrication by her mind in a response to fear.

ref_text:
Hope I got some brothers that outlive me
 They gon' tell the story, shit was different with me
tate_text:
Drake may be referring to his late OVO affiliate, Fif, who was gunned down in Toronto in September 2017. Drake later commemorated him with a tattoo of his face on his forearm a few days after his passing.



This may also refer to frequent collaborator, Lil Wayne, whom Drake considers a big brother. He has had a frequent history of almost deadly seizures heightened by his use of the narcotic, lean.

Since God is a central theme of the song, Drake could also be comparing the 12 Apostles and Jesus Christ, to his OVO crew members and himself. As Jesus Christ’s most devout disciples, the 12 Apostles were tasked with spreading the gospel of Jesus after his death.

Drake has not shied away from deifying himself using the alias ‘6 God’ in past tracks such as 6 God and 10 Bands:

I’m the real 6 God, boy

If his OVO crew members outlive him, they can tell the story of his rise to fame, much like the Apostles did for Jesus Christ post-mortem. If he happens to die and somebody outlives him in his crew, they can tell you who Drake was behind closed doors, much better than what outside sources write up. That’s where “They gon' tell the story, shit was different with me” comes from.

However, once Drake got bigger and started separating himself from his Toronto peers, artists like Tory started to show dislike. Drake noticed this and realized Tory’s true feelings towards him. It goes to show that Drake will stick to his “No New Friends” policy and focus on his business.

Where them niggas don't aim, they just palm Berettas (bang)
 And bomb whatever, say we don't move calmly, never (no)
tate_text:
Beretta is an Italian firearm manufacturer, whose weapons, mostly pistols, are commonly used among gang members.

To “palm” something is to hold it, and so Joey seems to be claiming people from Brooklyn carry dual Berettas, hindering your aiming ability, but gifting the ability to shoot faster and cause more damage, with a very “shoot now, worry later” mentality.



He extends on that mentality and wraps up this bar by stating that him and his people would rather destroy everything than try and be calm and avoid conflict.

‘Bomb’ is a common graffiti term meaning to write on a lot of places quickly, further creating this image of unruliness and chaos across Brooklyn.

They tell me “What’s done in the dark
Will find a way to shine”

Because Cole is not normally a querulous person, he allows time to expose his Demons rather than doing it forcibly. However, he also cares greatly about his pride which is in jeopardy due to his Demons. He discusses allowing Demons to exist at the expense of pride on “Motiv8”:

Too many times I swallowed my pride
Get money
I’m crackin' a smile, I’m dyin' inside
My demons are close, I’m tryin' to hide

ref_text:
Shut the fuck up, you sound like the last nigga I know
 Might end up like the last nigga I know
 Oh, you don't wanna clash? Nigga, I know
tate_text:
“The last nigga I know,” may be a shot at Jay Electronica. Jay dissed Kendrick in a video, calling him lame and his son. He refused to play his music and said he didn’t like any of it except “Cartoons and Cereal.” After Ab-Soul dissed him, Jay backpedalled and posted a video saying he would collab with Kendrick, showing he didn’t want confrontation.

Kendrick may have dissed Jay before on “untitled 7:”

I can never end a career if it never start

Terrace Martin later denied that “untitled 7” was directed at Jay.

“You don’t wanna clash,” may also be a minor slight at Drake, who’s a big fan of the U.K. grime scene. Kendrick uses the word “clash” instead of “battle,” to highlight his awareness of Drake’s tendency to borrow U.K. slang.

ref_text: And can't arrive at a compromise so it's Black Ops
tate_text:
This is a wordplay on the elite, covert missions the government doesn’t want you to know about (Black Operations) and the fact that black Americans are stuck at an impasse with the police force. Despite acknowledging that violence achieves very little for the social justice, Em (as a black male) ultimately feels that he is faced with no other choice, so they might as well arm up and go to war.



The phrase “Black Ops” entered the vernacular mostly due to the popularity of the Call of Duty: Black Ops video game series. Em’s track “Survival” premiered as a pre-order bonus for Call of Duty: Ghosts (2013).

ref_text: But along with celebrity comes about 70 shots to your frame
tate_text:
Jay would reference Big’s classic track more explicitly later in the album, but here he uses it as an aggressive statement.

More Money More Problems. Jay is famous for his subliminal disses, and his ability to remain calm and collected when being attacked from all sides. He only explicitly goes after the big fish.

It’s hard to do when you’ve got nothing to prove
Everybody know you better, you in a lose lose
Cause even when you win, ultimately you lose
Real niggas like, “Why Hov talking to Dude?”

His claim here is that by going at Nas hard on wax in this verse, he is bringing him in to the spotlight. During his Breakfast Club interview Charlemagne remarked that the beef “helped Nas”. Jay is sending a warning though: with great fame comes great danger.

ref_text: I flip my misfortune and grow me a fortune
tate_text:
The “misfortune” he refers to is likely the impoverished circumstances in which he was raised, as he spent part of his childhood living in a Fayetteville trailer park.  Cole discusses such an upbringing in his 2014 interview with Music Times:

There were days when my mom would have to scrape up nickels and dimes to give me $1.50 lunch money,“ Cole said. "And I would know she wasn’t eating lunch that day so that I could.

He transformed or, “flipped” such misfortune into a fortune, as his impoverished upbringing provided him with material for his music, but it also instilled in him a hunger to overcome the odds and make it in the rap game. While Cole never actually sold drugs himself, they were all around him growing up, hence the album’s drug and addiction theme. So it’s possible the “misfortune” he refers to is not just about being broke, but about about growing up around drugs and dealers, specifically. From this perspective, “flip” refers to the buying and reselling of drugs for profit. This is actually the 2nd time on this album that he’s rapped about flipping drugs, with the first being on the track, “KOD” where he raps:

This is what you call a flip
Ten keys from a quarter brick
Bentley from his mama’s whip

ref_text: [Part II: "I'm Dying of Thirst"]
tate_text:
This is a deeper thirst of the soul that, ironically, “Swimming Pools” of alcohol will never quench.  Rather, Kendrick needs the baptismal pool to cleanse his soul from sin.



As St. Paul details in verses 3-4 of Romans 6, the baptismal waters represent, when one is plunged beneath them, identification with Jesus in his crucifixion, death to sin, and a subsequent resurrection into life with Christ.

ref_text:
And I'ma lean, 'til I fall, ooh yeah
 And I don’t give a damn
 I felt the ground before
tate_text:
He’s on that sizzurp, so he’s leanin', and he’ll do it until he passes out, and isn’t worried because he frequently is on codeine.



“Lean until I fall” a double entendre: He also refers to pushing the limits in his life.  His ultra-rapid rise to stardom has literally made him a wealthy, jet-setting sensation overnight – sitting courtside at basketball games.

This rapid increase in status and wealth took place so quickly that he can still remember what it was like to be a poor, struggling artist, and it wasn’t that bad.  So he is prepared to push it all to the limit, go too far, or too hard, even at the risk of losing it all, because he’s been there before.

The Weeknd also refers to this line on “The Fall”.
