ref_text:
The sky darkens, my life flashes, the plane that I was
 Supposed to be on crashes and burns to ashes
tate_text:
This tragic image causes Em to wake up from his dream/nightmare and be with his daughter.

The plane crashing symbolizes the road/journey Eminem was on. So he is saying that his life was going down hill and would crash and burn if he did/does not change.

Since it’s the plane he was “supposed to be on”, this line further emphasizes his inevitable death, as it portrays how he would’ve died regardless of shooting himself.

ref_text: I will fight for this land
tate_text:
Hamilton, like most immigrants, adopted his new country. He tried to leave his past on Nevis, and not bring it to America.

Am I then more of an American than those who drew their first breath on American ground?

Alexander Hamilton to Rufus King, February 21, 1795

Hamilton so fully adopted his new country that he fought in the war, and fully invested in the “democracy experiment.”

So go ahead and talk your talk
 'Cause I won't take the bait
 I'm over here doin' what I like
 I'm over here workin' day and night
 And if my real ain't real enough
 I'm sorry for you, bae
tate_text:
Detractors claim that Ariana is fake because her reported real-life behavior doesn’t jibe with her interviews and songs. For example, gossip pages have reported that Ariana’s “life coach” quit because of her selfish  attitude, and that her signature ponytail was actually a hair extension.

The word “bae” at the end of the verse hints that this may be about her short-lived relationship with Big Sean. Ariana is passionate about her career, and she doesn’t have the time or energy to maintain a difficult relationship. This echoes Big Sean’s account of their breakup. He stated that the relationship was somewhat one-sided, and that she didn’t want to put any effort into saving the relationship.

Either way, Ariana doesn’t let the negative opinions of others affect her.

I got one less problem without ya
I got one less problem without ya
(I got one less, one less problem)

ref_text:
Click, click, click and post
 Drip-drip-dripped in gold
tate_text:
This describes the clicking of a camera and “posting” of the picture or video on social media. For example, Ariana first confirmed her relationship with Mac Miller in an Instagram post, with the caption:

baabyyy

Throughout the rest of their relationship, they both kept sharing pictures and videos of themselves on Instagram and Snapchat.

Ariana shared one final video of her and Mac one week after he unfortunately passed away due to an overdose.

On the other side, “Drip” is slang referring to jewellery or clothes.

The line was also teased on Grande’s Twitter a few hours prior to the release of the song.

ref_text: You keep me in your orbit
tate_text:
In astronomy, an orbit refers to a circular path followed around a celestial body. For example, the Earth is known to orbit around the sun.



Mac was a central figure in Ariana’s life, and her life in many ways revolved around him.

Scientifically, the earth orbits the Sun due to the gravitational pull of the sun. Similarly, Ariana is inexplicably drawn to Mac – and can’t simply let go of him – even if he hurts her. Interestingly, lighter objects will always orbit heavier ones which is telling in this tale of toxic relationships. Mac’s struggle with drugs and alcohol may have placed a heavy burden on him, with Ariana hoping to be a light source, lifting some of that weight.

ref_text:
We was together on the block since free lunch
 We shoulda been together havin' Four Seasons brunch
tate_text:
They’ve been together since back when they were in school. They were poor so they qualified for free lunches.

Jay-Z shows regret that he’s had to leave this girl behind as he has become successful. That free lunch they used to have should have progressed into the more luxurious brunch at Four Seasons Hotel that Jay-Z has become accustomed to.



“Four Seasons” is a double entendre symbolizing both money and time. As explained above, brunch at Four Seasons equals luxury, which is the byproduct of money.

Four seasons is also an indicator of time. One set of four seasons is a year, but this is plural indicating several years. If they had been together for the whole time that they knew each other they would have had years worth of brunches together.

ref_text:
I don't wanna hear you lie tonight
 Now that I've become who I really am
tate_text:
Ari’s tired of his BS and now that she has opened her eyes and embraced who she really is, she’s seeing that this guy is only gonna cause her pain.

In an Times interview, Ariana made it clear that “I’ve become who I really are” is grammarly incorrect, along with “I only wanna die alive”. Her producer, Max Martin, insisted:

I fought him on it the whole time. “I am not going to sing a grammatically incorrect lyric, help me, God!” Max was like, “It’s funny — just do it!” I know it’s funny and silly, but grammatically incorrect things make me cringe sometimes.

Of course, she gave in:

I was like, whatever, let’s do it and have some fun. I need to shake it off and let it go and be a little less rigid and old. I’m like 90. I need to not be that old.

ref_text:
Mike WiLL the one who made it
 It's Shady on the lyrics
tate_text:
Mike WiLL Made-It is a producer from Atlanta. Early in his career, Mike WiLL Made-It, who was then known as “Mike Will,” produced Gucci Mane’s track “Star Status,” where Gucci raps:

Mike Will made it, Gucci Mane slayed it

Gucci’s line gave Mike WiLL a lot of exposure, and eventually he changed his name to include the “Made-It,” and has since then used different versions of the line as his producer tag.

In early 2018, shortly after the release of Revival, a picture and some social media videos surfaced of Mike WiLL Made-It, Dr. Dre, and Eminem in the studio:



“Shady on the lyrics” refers to Eminem’s alter ego, Slim Shady. Despite killing off the character on his 2005 track “When I’m Gone,” Eminem has rapped as Slim Shady in some form on each of his albums. Kamikaze is one of Eminem’s albums where Shady’s presence is most obvious.

ref_text:
She like "Don't you know this shit already?
 Nigga, ain't you rich already?"
 Yeah, but I got dumb as shit
 Hanging 'round these rappers cause they dumb as shit
tate_text:
If Cole did go back to university, people would wonder why. The girl would say “Don’t you know this shit already?” because he already graduated (from St. John’s University, Magna Cum Laude). She would say “Nigga ain’t you rich already?” because he has already made it in the rap game. She thinks he should already know the material and should be focusing on his rap career.

He claims that hanging around with rappers has made him dumb. It’s a prejudice that most rappers are uneducated, but the fact is that Cole is one of only few rappers with a college degree. He feels like having lost the knowledge and intellect he had gained from graduating college, which is why in recent interviews you hear Cole say “I’m going back to college” with the intention to get smarter.

He certainly also understands getting smarter as an opportunity to enhance his lyrical abilities. He wants to write more songs with “smart” and “real” lyrics, instead of songs with “dumb” messages like “Work Out” only to sell records.

The girl sounds like the girl form “I’m a Fool”

She told me “Cole, I love you rode with you way before the riches
But you way too educated to be calling women bitches
And calling brothas niggas, pardon if I cross a line
But all this time knew you was different than all them other niggas”
I responded to her “please don’t put me on a pedestal
Cuz I know better and I’m still a fool”

ref_text: I have soldiers that will yield for you
tate_text:
Basically saying, “I have men who will take orders from you,” but the submissive connotation of “yield” suggests much more.

While it calls back to the Continental army troops ready to yield to Hamilton’s command from the previous line, this line reframes the context of “troops”, moving clearly into the OTHER troops waiting in the field, the British troops who are unknowingly waiting to be defeated.

ref_text: Been devoted to fuckin' up bundles of paper
tate_text:
“Fuckin' up bundles of paper” is a metaphor for making money and it also means he’s writing lyrics or taking notes. There are sounds of him “fuckin' up paper” by balling it up at the end of the song.

In December 2015, Kendrick told the New York Times:

I’m just writing, writing, writing.

The ideas of making money, writing lyrics and taking notes are all intertwined since Kendrick’s notes are transferred to songs and his songs make him money.

I bought every V12 engine
 Wish I could take it back to the beginnin'
tate_text:
A “V12” is a twelve cylinder engine found in vehicles like Ferraris, Lamborghinis, Aston Martins, and some Mercedes-Benzes. JAY-Z expressing his love for these cars and engines in his music dates back to his 2004 track “Allure”:

I’ve got a thing for the big-body Benzes, it dulls my senses
In love with a V-Dub engine

Jay wants to go back and purchase land and real estate, which appreciates in value, rather than purchasing cars that depreciate in value.
 The gentrification in his home city, Brooklyn, raised the property value.

ref_text:
Took me too long for this song, I don't deserve you
 I harassed you out in Paris
 "Please come back to Rome," you make it home
tate_text:
JAY-Z and Beyoncé, who have been together some fifteen years, often find themselves under the lens of the world media, and their relationship has regularly been beset by allegations of trouble and infidelity. This famously came to a head in 2016 when Beyoncé released her album Lemonade, which appeared to contain numerous references to her husbands alleged adultery.

Hov seems to confirm his infidelity here and numerous other times throughout 4:44. In the spirit of reconciliation, he concedes that it has taken him too long to offer his apologies—after all, the album dropped just over a year after Lemonade.

His references to Paris and Rome, both European capitals, underline the hectic, jet-setting lifestyle of a power couple made up of two of the planet’s biggest and most successful musical stars. It’s unlikely he is actually asking Beyoncé to join him in Rome, though. Instead, he may be indicating his longing for the strength he feels when he is happy and has his wife by his side; Rome is the historic centre of the Roman Empire, which seemed limitless in its influence at the height of its power.

ref_text:
Wouldn't you know
 We been hurt, been down before
 Nigga, when our pride was low
 Lookin' at the world like, "Where do we go?"
tate_text:
“Wouldn’t you know” is an English idiom used as a preface to express dismay at one’s situation. Lamar uses the idiom to introduce the material, emotional, and psychological consequences of being Black in America.

“Lookin' at the world like where do we go?” is an authentic question of action that is the primary referent underlying all studies of the African Diaspora.

Lamar suggests that identity conflicts and a lack of pride are often corresponding conditions. He draws a connection between the positive development of Black pride/power and the potential personal/social/political revolution that can arise from struggling.

This leads into the next lines about police hostility towards Black people and potential retributive violence (“my gun might blow.”)

tate_text:
In “Hello,” Cole explains that he doesn’t have a home. Now that he’s welcoming a child into the world, Cole tells his mother that he’s building a home back in Fayetteville, NC.

“Fit for a king” suggests that Jermaine’s home is luxurious. Perhaps a mansion, Cole’s house is fit for someone who can sing as large rooms absorb sound.

However, with a nice home comes a story of all the pain Cole went through to achieve it. From a trailer park to a front yard with trees in the sky, Cole had to work tremendously hard as an artist and producer to afford a home so large.

Especially if his neighbors think he’s selling drugs just to live where he currently resides.

ref_text:
Yeah, these days these new girls, they got me nervous
 They go to school and do bottle service
 They can't decide, they keep switchin' majors
 Being indecisive makes me anxious
tate_text:
Drake is getting older, believe it or not. It’s getting harder for him to relate to college girls, especially those that can’t decide on a major. Think about it. Drake is 28. College girls are stereotypically between 17-22. That’s an average difference of 8 & a half years. And it’s showing. You can’t deny that when a verse starts with, “These days…” it has an “Ahh, I remember the golden days…” ring to it. Another point of relevance, Drake says he’s “anxious” and “nervous”, emotions commonly associated with older people. The young are wild, free, and indecisive because they still have time, but maybe time is becoming the one luxury Drake cannot afford.

Also, “being indecisive makes me anxious” could be a double entendre wherein Drake is also referring to himself being indecisive, not just “these new girls”.

ref_text: I've been through the wringer
tate_text:
Triple Entendre

A wringer is an old fashioned device used to wring water from laundry. Being put through it would be a painful experience for a full grown adult. This serves as a metaphor for 3 things:


Any and every struggle and painful experience that he has been through: his dad leaving him when he was only 6 months old, his mom being an addict and suffering from Münchausen syndrome by proxy, his marriage with Kim being a wreck and then Proof’s death which led to his drug addiction.
Him kicking his drug addiction and coming out clean just like a wringer gets the water and everything dissolved in the water out of the clothes.
After sub-par albums Encore and Relapse people started to say that Eminem had got washed up but now he has been through the wringer and is dry, which means he is back in form.

ref_text: When you smile
tate_text:
Smiling is one of the first things that babies learn to do, and seeing that smile warms the heart of every parent.

But, of course, smiling also means something peculiar to Burr, whose “talk less, smile more” mantra means that his smile is usually calculated. Burr’s smile is associated with conceding defeat, repressing thoughts or opinions, or being satisfied enough to wait instead of act.

In contrast to all of that, Theodosia’s smile is purely due to genuine happiness, which is why Burr is so thrown by it, and, if one takes the cut reprise into account, it later becomes the reason he tries to get ahead.

ref_text: Peter Pan, Gucci fan, look at you, uh
tate_text:
Peter Pan is a fictional character originally created by novelist J. M. Barrie, later made popular by Walt Disney’s 1953 film Peter Pan. Peter’s main attribute is his inability to mature and grow up, along with his mischievous, careless, and adventurous persona.

His distinctly green outfit includes an accordingly green hat with a small red feather. It’s also worth noting that his hair is similarly red.



Gucci is a renowned Italian luxury brand that manufactures fashion products and leather goods. During World War II, Gucci sold bags made of canvas, distinguished by their signature double G logo with prominent red and green bands–since then, it is distinctly recognizable as a part of the brand. X compares the red and green of Peter’s hat to that of Gucci’s brand.

In the Dominican Republic, people speak Spanish. “inglés” means English en Español, while “comprende” means understanding.

When a Spanish-speaking person cannot comprehend English they might misinterpret words, but ironically, when they are presented with money, they will probably come to their senses pretty quickly. Money is often referred to as a “universal language”—everyone understands what it means.

tate_text:
As Cole welcomes his child into this world, he begins to question whether or not he is truly worthy of the monumental task that is being a father. For humans, and for most organic life, the most basic instinct is that of self preservation. Thus, our brains are automatically hardwired to make decisions that our in our own best interest. Yet, Cole recognizes, like all new parents, that as a father in certain situations he will have to put his daughter’s well being above his own.

This is a monumental moment in the album, as Cole’s newfound appreciation and understanding of fatherhood largely shape his final reflections on the life of his slain friend James and what made him a “real nigga.”

XXXTentacion was widely known for his lyrics discussing suicide and depression, with one of his most popular songs, “Jocelyn Flores” being dedicated to a friend of his who commit suicide. In an interview with XXL Magazine, X opened up about his personal experiences with depression. When asked what caused his depression, he stated:

We really have nobody, so I felt like with being placed away from [his mother] and then she having to pretty much hustle to help me, it was really being alone and being placed away from people I had any attachment to what made me what I am.

Mental illness is not often spoken about by celebrities or famous people, let alone rappers, so this set X apart from most mainstream artists. With this fame, he used his passion to help troubled teens and children, as he also discussed his goals for bettering his hometown community of Broward County, FL and Florida as a whole.

I’m gonna be doing a lot of investing and I really want to invest in a teenage therapy where every teenager that’s happy talks to another teenager that’s depressed… I want to give a donation to the foster homes in my state and give them PS4s and TVs and shit. I’m basically gonna try to run up my money as much as possible and give back to the community."

X has also uploaded a video documenting his efforts to charity to YouTube titled “THE HELPING HAND CHALLENGE”: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NKlEnMFQMgI

ref_text: Swish, swish, how long they keep you in court? All day, nigga
tate_text:
Kanye’s had multiple run-ins with the law and has subsequently spent some time in court. His line from “Mercy” – “you gon' see lawyers and niggas in Jordans” comes to mind.

Incidents include; Allegedly assaulting an 18 year old man in 2014 for attacking Kim and calling her a “n****r lover”, the case was later settled for more than $250,000. Fighting with a paparazzo in 2013, which resulted in him receiving 2 years probation, and 250 hours of community service and 30 days of anger management. Scuffling with a paparazzo at an airport in 2008 – Kanye received 50 hours of community service.

Apart from his troubles with the law, Kanye’s use of “swish, swish” doubles as a basketball and drug allusion. While a “swish” is when the ball lands clean through the hoop. For most inner city basketball games, the winner stays on the court, so if you are making swishes – you could be on the court all day.


“swishers” are used to roll blunts, something your P.O might get you in trouble for.




SWISH was also one of the earliest titles for Kanye’s 7th studio album, The Life of Pablo.

ref_text:
Throw a steak off the ark
 To a pool full of sharks, he'll take it
 Leave him in the wilderness
 With a sworn nemesis, he'll make it
 Take the gratitude from him
 I bet he'll show you somethin', whoa
tate_text:
These lines represent the mindset of young black males growing up in poverty stricken and crime infested areas.

Kendrick used the shark metaphor before on Dr. Dre’s 2015 song, “Deep Water,” a song that uses wildlife in the ocean as an analogy for gang culture in Compton:

They worry him to death, but he’s no vegetarian
The beef is on his breath, inheriting the drama better than
A great white, nigga, this is life in my aquarium

The idea is that the environment black males grow up in makes them more vicious than sharks.

“Ark” is another word for boat, but this could also be a reference to the story of Noah’s Ark in the Old Testament. Although Noah’s ark is about the obedience and faith of God’s servant, perhaps Kendrick uses the ark to symbolize wealth and privilege. If this is the case, the ark is home of the upper classes of society where people escape the “flood” of violence and crime that happen in lower class urban areas, which Kendrick refers to as “pool full of sharks.”

K.Dot also compares the youth to Jesus in the wilderness with his sworn nemesis, Satan. The Book of Matthew says:

Then Jesus was led up by the Spirit into the wilderness to be tempted by the devil

Kendrick’s narrative shows that certain people in harsh situations will find a way to survive, but stripping things away from them, including their “gratitude,” will result in them becoming ruthless and willing to kill, as the following lines suggest.

ref_text: [Produced by Kanye West, Mike Dean & Plain Pat]
tate_text:
The song begins with an ominous, distorted vocal roar, sung by Justin Vernon of Bon Iver, with Vernon declaring:

I shoot the lights out

Which sets up the dark atmosphere of the track. The intro of the song is followed by a brief verse given by Ross, delivered in the rapping style of boom bap with his deep voice complementing the beat. The song ends in a spooky, hoarse vocal riff delivered by Vernon, reminiscent of the track “Thriller”. An extended catchy vocal riff, closes the track.

The song heavily features bombastic tribal drums, and paranoia-inducing strings that create a feeling of tension. The beat of “Monster” has been described as a “hyperventilating death rattle”, the song was permeated with dark, urgent-sounding moans.



This monstrous beat has been reused for a freestyle by Kendrick Lamar, another by Nitty Scott and has been sampled numerous times. Interesting to note is that it’s one of the few beats, by Kanye standards, without a sample.

ref_text:
This house is not a home to you
 But you decide to go ahead and lay down, lay down
tate_text:
The whole song has a literal and figurative meaning. In regards to the literal one, his girl for the night is overstaying her welcome and is unaware of it. Even though his house is not her’s, she decides to “make herself at home.”

Figuratively, Abel is talking to all of his new fans now that he’s “gone mainstream.” He’s bringing us into his world, even though it’s uncomfortable to him after living a low-key life in Toronto. Nobody even knew what his face looked like when House of Balloons dropped.

ref_text: Write ev’rything down, far as I can see…
tate_text:
Double meaning here, especially in contrast to earlier: “Far as I can see” can simply refer to sight, literally, “the limit of one’s sight,” but it can also refer to events from one’s own perspective.  Earlier in the song it seems to use the former meaning, whereas here it uses the latter, equating the two to describe Hamilton’s current narrow-mindedness; the limit of his sight has become his own perspective, showing how he fails to consider the way others will react to the Reynolds Pamphlet.

It is also true to the historical Reynolds Pamphlet in that Alexander actually wrote a 90-page pamphlet, including every tiny detail about the two-year affair and scandal. “Everything as far as I can see”, indeed.

ref_text:
Man, I can understand how it might be
 Kinda hard to love a girl like me
 I don't blame you much for wanting to be free
 I just wanted you to know
tate_text:
Rihanna interpolates parts of the first verse of Nina Simone’s “Do What You Gotta Do.” The verse is sampled in the outro of the song.

The line “I don’t blame you much for wanting to be free,” feels like an answer to Kanye’s bridge in both “Father Stretch My Hands Pt. 1” and “Pt. 2”:

Just want to feel liberated, I, I, I
I just want to feel liberated, I, I, I
If I ever instigated I’m sorry
Tell me who in here can relate, I, I, I

These parts are a back and forth between Kanye and “fame.” During his early days as a producer, all Kanye wanted to be was famous, but no one would give him a chance. Now, he’s at the opposite end of the spectrum and his creativity is being held back because he’s a “celebrity.”

ref_text:
So satanic, K-Mart chains panic
 ‘Cause they can't even spin back the curse words
 ‘Cause they're worse when they're reversed, motherfucker
tate_text:
The spinning back refers to the way tracks used to be censored, by playing the curse words backwards, which was a technique used by DJs, when they would spin the actual record back.



Eminem has always been a fan of referencing Satan, which he does several times on this album in tracks like Rap God. He even has a song that has a feature from “Satan” to represent his battle with addiction and fame.

His version of ‘Satan’ also references what drives his art. His muse. Shady. It’s rage.

The following line has a backmasked portion, meaning a part of the line is recorded backwards. Many conspiracy theorists believe this is a method of brainwashing used by the Illuminati to hide Satanic references in music. The reversed version of the line sounds like Eminem is saying “Rape your mother, kill your parents!”, and the original is saying “Shit, motherfucker!”

https://soundcloud.com/randyy/tihs-rekcufrehtom

K-Mart and other retailers that would sell the CD would be panicking because they have no way to hide the curse words in Eminem’s music here. It’s common to spin back (reverse) vocals in rap to censor out words without chopping up the rapper’s flow, but either way it’s ineffective on this track. This is also a reference to his “K-Mart Mansion” which he bought from the former CEO of K-Mart.

ref_text: You makin' him nervous, the music is loud
tate_text:
Kayla Duckworth, Kendrick’s sister, voices this line. She also appeared at the end of 2015’s “Black Friday.”

Kendrick uses this line to give his dad a shoutout. When he was a newborn baby on his way home from the hospital, his dad was blasting Big Daddy Kane in the car, and his mother asked him to turn it down. His dad refused and said the loud music is good for him. Kendrick is attributing his skills and success in the music industry to his early exposure.

 Didn't know me, you were drawn in
 I was lost and beat up
tate_text:
Like Kanye, Sia was living the “wild life”. During a rare interview with Billboard in 2012, Sia spoke about burning out as an artist and only wanting to write songs for others:

I got seriously addicted to Vicodin and Oxycodone, and I was always a drinker but I didn’t know I was an alcoholic. I was really unhappy being an artist and I was getting sicker and sicker.

While she beat herself up, her loss was her boyfriend. He died in a traffic accident while she was in Thailand, one week before they were going to reunite for a trip around the world.

Coming full circle, Sia is most likely referring to herself as the person “she found”. As per Billboard in 2012:

Things improved after a misdiagnosis was corrected and Sia was treated for hyperthyroid disease. Her medication was switched and she rested. The pills and booze stopped, and she began doing exactly what she’d always wanted.

We found each other
 I helped you out of a broken place
 You gave me comfort
 But falling for you was my mistake
tate_text:
Abel is likely referring to his ex-girlfriend, Selena Gomez, whom he dated for 10 months. During this period, he helped her through her battle with Lupus, even canceling a few shows on his “Legend of the Fall” tour to be by her side.

According to an insider:

Abel has been one of her biggest supports. She had been traveling with him on his tour and he was off during her surgery and right after during her recovery.

Gomez also consistently appeared on Abel’s social handles. For example, during their vacation to Italy at the end of January, she appeared on his Instagram story.

The guitar strum and whistling both come from Paul McCartney’s “Two-Finger Chord & Whistle”. Paul wrote this song after viewing a print of Pablo Picasso’s The Old Guitarist while in the hospital for the birth of his second child, Mary.

ref_text:
On my way, on my way, on my way down
 On my way, on my way, on my way down
tate_text:
TLC starts this thing off by making an analogy between themselves and the sun—which, as everyone knows, rises and sets with daily regularity.  (Later in the opening verse they attribute an epistemological intention to this rhythm: “like the sun know”.)

So right away the song claims to be about the convergence of metaphysical truths (articulated in this case as a kind of astrological project—the sun in astrology represents “who you are” and in this opening hook TLC claim to be “on their way down,” i.e. on the wan of the sun’s arc) and physical truths (physics, the planets, etc.).

“On my way down” also has a semi-religious connotation that is echoed later in the song when Cole raps “we in hell already.”  One cannot help but think of Dante’s trek into the layered Inferno of the underworld, questing deeper and deeper——and this pseudo-religious interpretation is supported by the chant-like repetition of the main line …

ref_text: How does a
tate_text:
On the opening of lines of the show, Lin-Manuel Miranda said to CBS News 60 minutes with Charlie Rose:

Hamilton spoke in fluid paragraphs and he had density to his writing, and because of that the first line of the show is this huge run-on sentence.

Miranda has stated many times that because of this density and the sheer magnitude of Hamilton’s writings, hip-hop is uniquely suited to tell his story, as it can fit more words per measure than any other musical genre. In this way, Burr is prefacing what the audience’s ear will be subject to for the rest of the show.

This line is also the first use of a motif signaling major transitions in Hamilton’s life (e.g. in “A Winter’s Ball,” signaling his transition from bachelorhood to married life, or in “The Adams Administration,” signaling his transition from prominence and respectability to infamy and disfavor). In this instance, it signals his transition from a penniless orphan with no prospects to a new immigrant with nowhere to go but up.

ref_text:
Hit the prez with a Cuban link on my neck
 Uneducated, but I got a million-dollar check like that
tate_text:
Less than a year after making this boast, Kendrick would find himself invited for a one-on-one with Obama in the Oval Office, in which they spoke about Kendrick’s work with children, racial issues, and—just maybe— the president’s favorite song of the year.



Kendrick is definitely wearing a chain in their meeting, but it appears to be a bit more modest than the broader style of the classic Cuban link.

The second line, as referenced in the Genius interview with Kendrick about this album, shows how Kendrick is deeply troubled by the fact that in today’s school system, kids are taught about many things which they will never need in life but not about important, practical life lessons such as handling money and paying taxes. This plays into the song and the album as a whole, as Wesley Snipes is the example given in this song of someone who wasn’t educated on what they could and could not do with taxes and suffered the consequences.

ref_text:
I know that it's difficult
 I'm stackin' this paper, it's sort of habitual
tate_text:
It’s difficult for some people to comprehend and accept that he’s making money from his talents because they’re envious, and he’s not able to see it from the outside, since his fortune is the fruit of countless hours of hard work.

But at the same time, he could also be saying that accumulating wealth is extremely difficult, and it’s even harder to maintain that wealth. Cole acknowledged how hard it is to become rich in his verse on Jeezy’s “American Dream”:

ref_text:
Oh Lord, got a whole lot to show for it
 I mean we can really get it, we can go for it
tate_text:
All those late nights in the studio have paid off tremendously for Drake. Initially, he received buzz from his So Far Gone mixtape; since then, he has blossomed into one of the leading figures in rap today.

After the success of his platinum debut album, he followed it with his Grammy winning sophmore, Take Care. His singles are just as successful. He broke the record for most #1 Rap singles on the Billboard Charts, as well as creating a way of life with the term “YOLO”. So as you can see Drake does have a whole lot to show for his success.

ref_text: Gonna be that one? And then once we get 'em, it's never the same
tate_text:
When people fall in love, all sorts of ideals are created and projected onto the ones that they love – until it is slowly realized the individual with which they fell in love with does not in the slightest meet those ideals

In reference to drug addiction, once someone gets addicted, he/she remembers the high the drug created and hopes to create it again by acquiring it again, but with continuous use, the highs created require more and more of the drug – meaning the original amount of the drug does not live up to the hopes of the addict.
When you get the person back after losing him/her, that person who comes back is never the same neither are you.

He could be talking about the hiphop world also. Like in the song “Almost Famous”, he said he always want to be famous, but when he’s already famous (like recently) he felt like it’s not as what he thought it would feel like. He lost his freedom (like in the song “Marshall Mathers” or “25 to life”)

ref_text: My manager back in the days was racist
tate_text:
He suggests by the following line that, in this line, he is referring to the manager he had as a teenager working at a skating rink.

He has since moved on to Mark Pitts, who has managed Biggie and Nas, and now also manages Miguel, who’s collaborated with Cole on “All I Want is You” and “Power Trip”.

Mark seems to respect Cole for his artistry and personal qualities. He had this to say:

I was going to stop managing hip-hop. I’d been through so much, from Big to Shyne to Nas. But J.Cole brought me back. It wasn’t just how he was an artist. Seeing where his head was at was a pleasure; it made me want to take him to another level.

Calling out the people who said that Eminem and Lil Wayne weren’t good, or that Eminem’s career was over. The haters won’t get any love now that both of them are back on top of their game.

What comes around goes around means that whatever you do in this life to others, whether it is good or bad, the same will return to you. Meaning, they will pay for having shown him only hate.

tate_text:
To “gas” someone up is to fire them up, to pump them up, to convince them to act in a certain manner.

Jay explained that his own crew was gassing him up to go at Prodigy.

Notice the figurative similarity between the words “ass” and “clap.”

Everybody wanted it to happen, like they did! There was a time like everybody was like ‘please, please let this guy go away’

He re-ups on the final line from the first verse. This isn’t just rap music, this is Jay’s life and livelihood. He will kill you.

ref_text:
Bitch, don't kill my vibe! Bitch, don't kill my vibe!
 Bitch, don't kill my vibe! Bitch, don't kill my vibe!
tate_text:
Kendrick is trying to chill – he doesn’t mind if you are around, just don’t fuck up his mood.

But to further this conjecture, this song hook is a complex revelation of Kendrick’s true psychology and the chorus is actually a declaration of his attitude towards the world.

Kendrick is a diverse person, and there are many layers to his personality. He is spiritual, accepting and thoughtful, but he also comes from a city of violence, drugs, crime, etc. Kendrick is an incredibly empathic person; he sees things from all points of view and thus does not fall into any specific classification but rather covers the entire spectrum of humanity. Because of his debilitating empathy, there is a slight distance between himself and his peers. He lives in his own kind of world, observing the behavior and the nature of everything and everyone around him and contemplating it to himself. He is sincere and stable and his ultimate quest is to spread peace.

However, a common tendency for people of this personality-type is to shy away from complex, inexplicable situations where no fair and amicable solution is apparent. When such scenarios occur they may try to retreat into their metaphysical bubble and escape the paradoxical anxieties of life. This is exactly what Kendrick demonstrates in this song (either consciously or subconsciously), and the phrase “Bitch Don’t Kill My Vibe” is a solemn declaration of his desire to attain peace when things cannot be resolved easily.

If it's meant to be, then it'll be
 If it's not, then fuck it, I'ma try
 Ain't no need to ask the Father why, no
tate_text:
“If it’s meant to be, it will be” is a popular expression meant to emphasize the importance of not worrying too much about the outcome of events. While sometimes people rely on fate to sort things out, Cole isn’t entirely content to sit back and wait for things to happen.

Jermaine is determined to work hard for what he wants, so even if it isn’t meant to be, he is still going to give it his best effort.

Whether the outcome is good or bad, there’s no need to question God (the Father), as everything in life, including death is meant to happen. Cole has touched on his relationship with God previously in “Apparently”.

tate_text:
This describes the anxiety of approaching someone attractive, a feeling that Cole has much personal experience with. In songs like “‘03 Adolescence”, he raps:

In love with the baddest girl in the city, I wish I knew her
I wish I won’t so shy, I wish I was a bit more fly

To “shoot one’s shot” is another phrase for asking someone out. Cole connects this to “brick”, a basketball term for a terribly shot ball that hits the backboard or the rim:



The narrator fails whenever he attempts to pursue someone, leading him to think he isn’t fit for romance. This insecurity contrasts with his friends' confidence in their “slick” flirting skills.

“I put my heart in a click” ties together the overall message of how social media has influenced finding love. Since he’s uncomfortable approaching this girl, the narrator expresses affection through liking (clicking) her photos.

tate_text:
Although Cole is recognized as one of the most relatable rappers for his honesty in documenting his struggle and ambitions, there are some things he keeps to himself. On “Too Deep For The Intro”, he raps:

I gotta make a move, I gotta do this now
If they don’t know your dreams, then they can’t shoot em down

While his dreams could win Oscars, some may not be as engaging to others and so they physically wouldn’t have experienced the same pain Cole went through, be it seeing his house foreclose or witnessing his mom become a crack addict.

ref_text:
But I'm aggravated without it
 My saddest days are without it
 My Saturdays are the loudest
 I'm blowing strong
tate_text:
The narrator has become so addicted to his druggy habits that he can’t be content without them. Both depression and constant aggravation are common side affects of Marijuana withdrawals and he’s clearly going through both.

“My Saturdays are the loudest” is likely a play on “loud,” a term for potent weed. The narrator spends his weekends getting high, which repeats the cycle of withdrawal.



It’s worth noting that these lines correlate with the album’s release date of April 20th, also known as 4/20, a universally celebrated day dedicated to weed.

ref_text: Blame it on the strain that you feel when daddy missing
tate_text:
Fatherlessness is a big issue in the black community, as many black children grow up without a father due to incarceration, death, or simply the abandonment of responsibility.

This is a double entendre, as “strain” can both mean stress and a breed of marijuana. Given the theme of self-medicating that is prevalent throughout the track, it can be assumed that this was overt.

Cole himself was raised by a single mother after his father abandoned the family.

This outro samples Section 25’s 1981 song, “Hit.”

The band have since responded to the sample. Vincent, the drummer, told Rolling Stone:

I understand, you got a hunnid bands
 You got a baby Benz, you got some bad friends
tate_text:
A band is $1000 in notes, tied with a rubber band. So a “hunnid bands” is a hundred thousand dollars.

A “Baby Benz” is a Mercedes C-Class or CLA, which are the entry models in the Mercedes-Benz line up. They start from around $35,000 CAD.



These lyrics follow the song’s theme of female empowerment. Drake knows this woman is self-made, and also understands women sometimes do not receive as much merit for their accomplishments. Men are typically portrayed as the breadwinners in a relationship, but Drake knows how hard this woman had to work in order to get to where she is now.

In her vlog, Ariana asks people to stop judging and find the light inside us all.

You focus on what you think people should be like for you. But when you stop and actually focus on them, you see the light in them. When you focus on me, you see the light in me. When we focus on each other, we see the light in each other. And even if you don’t, this is who we are. What are we making fun of? What’s there to make fun of? We should apologize for that.

ref_text: If Jeezy's payin' LeBron, I'm payin' Dwyane Wade
tate_text:
This is when I felt like I made it in pop culture. Once Jay Z did it, I felt like I was on that respect level of artists that I respect. I remember where I was, I was with my guys and we were hanging out and somebody texted me like, “Yo, listen to this song.” So I listened to it and then when I heard it, I’m like, “Did he just say what I think he said?”

It’s a lot of different references and obviously Jay Z has his own. Some people from the street have a street reference to it. So I don’t really know. I just know Jeezy came out with that song about Kobe and LeBron, “23, 24” and then he came back and said that. So I didn’t care what it was about. I was just glad that my name was associated in a big song like that, for the city of New York. It’s huge.

You know, when you’re young, you put your name in songs. You’re like “Oh, my name would sound right, there.” So when I first got in the league, I was like, “If I could just get one big artist to say my name, that would be so cool. That would be dope.” And I got a few not only just mention my name, but really be punchlines in songs and I think that’s the dopest part of it. For someone to sit down and write a classic that is going to be a hit, and think about putting you in there as a punchline, that’s pretty special.

All night long
 Sweet love all night long
 Sweet love all night long
 Sweet love all night long
 All I wanna, ain't no other
 We together, I remember
 Sweet love all night long
tate_text:
Beyoncé wants her partner by her side all night long together, and not to be with anyone else.

Don’t stop loving ‘til the morning, don’t stop loving 'til the morning

Similar to the hook on “Drunk In Love”

We be all night
We be all night, love, love
We be all night, love, love

In contrast to the message on “Drunk In Love”, which was one of violent and passionate sex, this is a much more intimate proposal. “Sweet love” and “All I wanna, ain’t no other” suggest that despite infidelity, there’s really no other lover Bey could see herself with.

 So many relatives tellin' us, sellin' us devilish works
 Killin' us, crime, intelligent, felonious
 Prevalent proposition with 9's
tate_text:
The mid-80s had some of the highest violent crime rates Compton has ever experienced.

The term ‘gears of war’ refers to people being used as part of one big machine of war. At that time gang crime was so prevalent that simply being affiliated with a gang member made you part of the fight.

Not only this, but it was impossible to avoid gang members as they were in every family. Members of your family that were smart, those which had been to prison, all of them trying to get you to join them in criminal activity. A nine refers to a 9mm pistol.

In “Poe Man’s Dreams,” Kendrick talks about his family being tied to criminal activity:

Since my uncles was institutionalized My intuition had said I was suited for family ties

ref_text: But damn, it’s getting dark, so let me spell out the name
tate_text: Hamilton is on the search for an identity, a chance for greatness in the New World of opportunity. However, as of yet, the young visionary is virtually a nobody, with a lot to say but no one willing to pay attention. His limited recognition amounts to just a “spark” right now, but rather than waiting for it to naturally develop into a sustainable flame, Hamilton grows impatient and fearful of the encroaching darkness. Not only is night falling within the setting of the number, making him literally less visible to those he’s trying to meet, but Hamilton’s constant awareness of his impending death makes him fear that he’s “running out of time.” So, he skips ahead in his own introduction, raising his voice to “spell out [his] name"—figuratively, making his identity known and cementing his legacy before his end.

ref_text:
Left him with nothin' but ruined pride, something new inside
 A voice saying
tate_text:
Peter left everything he had to his mistress and son. Though his father (and their grandfather) James Lytton advocated for Alexander and his brother, legal issues prevented them from receiving any support from Peter’s estate.

Moreover, their grandfather also died soon after this, and also left no provisions for Alexander or his brother in his will. All he’d been able to do for the young Alexander was make sure Hamilton got to keep his books after their mother’s death:

While he was awaiting settlement of the small estate—principally Rachel’s slaves and a stock of business supplies—the court auctioned off her personal effects. James Lytton considerately bought back for Alexander his trove of books.

Since Lytton had shown kindness to Alexander before, he must have felt betrayed on top of mourning all of his lost family members. These events motivated Hamilton to try to make his own way using his intelligence and writing skills. The books and treatises he retreated to read were the sum total of his small inheritance, just barely salvaged out of death and debt. He made the fullest use he could out of them.

Eminem destroys his tracks, but he might be crossing the line at the same time. There is a certain trade-off between his abilities as an artist, and his conscienceless lyrics that might hurt people on the receiving end. Matthew is the personification of Marshall Mathers' conscience.

The lack of conscience is a reference to his other self: Slim Shady. This could be foreshadowing the last track, Evil Twin.

ref_text: [Video directed by Jake Nava]
tate_text:
The “Monster” music video was released in June 2011, seven months following a leak of the unfinished product (which almost made Kanye shelve it). It features all four rappers amongst the midsts of sheer gore, primarily the corpses of white models – a potential stab at Ye’s then-recent ex Amber Rose. This could also be a satire of video vixens: instead of dancing attractive women, they’ve all been massacred. Lovely.

Directed by Jake Nava, best known for his work with Beyoncé, the video has been interpreted as a multitude of tributes to classic horror films such as Saw, American Psycho and Michael Jackson’s “Thriller” video. There are also some more obscure references to the character of Doctor Frankenstein and Bill Stoneham’s “The Hands Resist Him”.



The depicted misogyny and gothic style garnered a huge amount of controversy. The video was banned from MTV, alongside a backlash from activist Ann Simonton who started a petition to have it removed from online circulation. However, there has been some support for the piece. Brandon Soderburg argued for Kanye’s freedom of artistic expression, so not to dilute the effect.

ref_text:
"Forget Barbie, fuck Nicki 'cause she's fake"
 "She on a diet," but my pockets eating cheesecake
tate_text:
Nicki takes on the voice of her critics in these two lines. They complain about her fake character, claiming she puts on this face for her fans but in reality is like a diet cheater, stuffing cheesecake into her pants.

There is a double meaning here as cheese is another term for money. Her pockets are fat (rich) while she remains skinny and successful, like Barbie.

ref_text:
So stop with that childish shit, nigga, I'm grown
 Please leave it alone, don't throw rocks at the throne
tate_text:
This may seem like a paradoxical line in a song where he calls someone garbage and lame, but it indicates two things.

Firstly, don’t forget Jay sonning Prodigy in the first verse. Verse 4 is about his position in the rap game. It’s testament to the power of Nas that he even has Jay defending himself, considering the first song on the album is entitled “The Ruler’s Back”. His maturity will ultimately fail him, but for now he claims the higher road.

Secondly, he was about to embark on a campaign to “upgrade” his style and image. On The Black Album his track “Change Clothes” was pivotal in a culture shift in hip hop. At the time, he was saying “I am dismissing you and moving on to bigger and better things”. It didn’t quite pan out that way.

Jay would embrace his Ruler status on Watch The Throne in 2011 with Kanye.

Swizz Beatz is a legendary hip hop producer best known for his work with the likes of DMX, The LOX, and Kanye’s big brother Jay Z, as well as for being married to Alicia Keys.

At the 2007 Hot 97’s Summer Jam, Kanye showed up in the middle of Swizz’s set to challenge him to a duel of productions in order to decide who the better producer of the two was:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=843WSznP2CY

It appears Kanye deferred to Swizz, later calling him “the best rap producer of all time” and having him sing the hook to the My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy posse cut “So Appalled.” So if Swizz wants to savor the beat, Kanye isn’t going to get in the way of that.

tate_text:
https://soundcloud.com/rapgenius/kendrick-on

Reeking the scent – yeah, reeking the scent. Basically coming to grips with reality, saying I’m a teenager, I am out here, and there is possibly a chance that I won’t see tomorrow, so looking in the mirror and really understanding that was a tough point to deal with, a tough time to deal with. I could walk out there – there was one particular summer that was so hot you couldn’t even walk to the corner because the neighborhoods was feuding that crazy. If you walked to the corner for sure you were going to run into some action because somebody is on the other end of the corner, waiting for you to walk on that corner. That is how crazy Compton is, you know. You are waiting on that corner, you pull up, they hop out, shoot at you down the block so that you could run the opposite way, and have another car waiting on you as soon as you get to the corner, and that’s it for you. You ain’t got nowhere to go, you feel me? And you come to grips with that. You look in the mirror and say damn, this might be my last day walking out here as a teenager, you feel me? That is what that particular line, and that whole verse, is about really – grasping the idea of death, for a kid.

ref_text: [Produced by J. Cole]
tate_text:
This song samples “Mariya” by Family Circle (listen below) and “Impeach the President” by The Honey Drippers.

Cole isn’t the first to rap over either of these samples: “Like Father, Like Son” by The Game also samples “Mariya”, and “Impeach the President” has been sampled by many hip hop artists, all the way back to 2Pac’s “Just Like Daddy.”

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XzZ8mBZ8awA

Youtuber Sandurz made a step-by-step breakdown of the beat. You can check it out here!

ref_text: [Produced by Eminem]
tate_text:
From Angry Blonde:

“The Way I Am” was one of the few tracks that I did completely by myself. I had the beat in my head before I went into the studio to lay it down. I had the rhyme and the piano loop all worked out. I had Jeff [Bass] play the loop and I finished the rhyme listening to my headphone set on the way to L.A. That’s why the flow is like that, cause all I had was the piano loop in my headphones. I wanted to do some different shit. I thought about the rhymes first. Once I got the third line I didn’t want the cadence of the rhyme to stop going with the piano. Even if I took a break with rappin, I made the words echo so that they still went with the piano.

ref_text: Tell Adidas that we need a million in production
tate_text:
The demand for Kanye’s Yeezy Boosts released in 2015 was unprecedented, resulting in vastly inflated eBay prices for brand new pairs. During the launch of his 350’s, Adidas promoted an app as the best way to snag a pair. The only problem was, demand broke the app.

It’s been a constant struggle for him to set up the infrastructure to support such demand, and as a result he claims prices have been greatly inflated. This has been a barrier to growth as a fashion designer, with labels only interested in utilising his hip hop fame, rather than his design ability.

It’s very difficult if you don’t have that production and that experience that Ralph has, and it’s really difficult to get those price points, you know the Zara and H&M price points if you don’t got the factories, if you don’t got the boats.

His Adidas deal gives him the freedom to expand production.

I’m going to be the first hip-hop designer, and because of that I’mma be bigger than Wal-Mart.

The demand for Yeezys has been incredible; everyone wants to get their hands on them (they even sold out in less than 12 minutes).

Everybody doin' chick joints
 Probably rob these little dudes at fist point
tate_text:
Royce comments on how today’s rappers aren’t as tough as their predecessors and make music that caters excessively to a female audience.

“Little dudes” is likely an allusion to the rappers that use “Lil” as the prefix for their stage name. “Lil” rappers have become a common scapegoat for contemporary hip-hop at large. J. Cole made similar remarks on “1985,” as did Eminem on “The Ringer,” Kamikaze’s opener:

Lil Pump, Lil Xan imitate Lil Wayne
I should aim at everybody in the game, pick a name

Rather than robbing them with a weapon at gunpoint or knife-point, Royce believes that today’s rappers are so spineless that he can rob them with his bare hands.

ref_text:
It's not funny anymore, try different jokes
 Tell 'em hug and kiss my ass, X and O
 And kiss the ring while they at it,
tate_text:
Kanye is tired of all these people still blaming him for the Taylor Swift incident, or laughing at him for the famous South Park episode.

Kanye could also be quoting the aforementioned “people” and “his guy” who are telling him that he isn’t funny anymore. Kanye disagrees though… To prove them wrong, he tells another “joke: kiss my ass!

X & O have traditionally signified kisses and hugs, respectively. He repeats this mantra in “Power” – first to kiss his ass, then his asshole. It’s also a nice play on words, the “X” being the kiss and the ring being the “O”.

In the olden days of royalty, it was customary to kiss the king/queen’s ring as a sign of respect and deference to their sovereignty. Kanye however, is referring to another type of “ring”, that is not on his finger.

The two fell off after personal problems with X not liking Drake and Trippie beefing with 6ix9ine. Trippie working with Drake and X talking to 6ix9ine didn’t add up to the loyalty of their friendship and of course, the two don’t see eye to eye.

X has a track called “Pain = BESTFRIEND,” which was made back in March 2018 for his album ?, the song may be hinting at possible masochistic feelings.

ref_text:
She say, "Do you love me?" I tell her, "Only partly
 I only love my bed and my mama, I'm sorry"
tate_text:
Drake has a very close relationship with his mom, Sandi Graham. In the past, he’s referred to himself as a “momma’s boy.” Drake frequently mentions his mom in his songs, and even dedicated his 2015 track “You & The 6” to her.



Drake had previously mentioned not getting much sleep on “9,” “Gyalchester,” and “Do Not Disturb." He also spoke about his lack of rest in a toast during his 30th birthday. The limited rest time he gets makes him appreciate his bed even more.

Drake referenced this line in an Instagram post dedicated to his mom on her 58th birthday, as well as in an image he posted two days following the release of “God’s Plan.”

tate_text:
As seen in CW: SS, before acquiring fame, Cole placed his importances on money and being in the limelight. After realizing that those things wouldn’t fulfill him, but rather exhaust him, Cole began to place his values on love.

In “She’s Mine, Pt. 1,” Cole expresses his fear of exposing his most personal thoughts, though as the album plot continues, he feels comfortable telling the truth. So comfy that he’ll even sing them until he runs out of breath.

ref_text:
I'll ride through your cul-de-sac
 Window cracked, bumpin' your reference tracks
 Y-You collaborative effort rap, I-I have never said his raps
tate_text:
A reference track is a professionally mixed and mastered song, used by producers and artists as a standard to measure their own work against. The track that is chosen needs to have a similar vibe, sound and feeling to what the artist is trying to accomplish.

Although reference tracks are supposed to be used to ensure good mixing and mastering, Em is implying it might lead to plagiarism. This leads to an abundance of tracks that sound alike. Secondly, Em could be saying that he prefer the original reference track to the new release.

With “collaborative effort”, Em refers to the controversial use of ghostwriters in hip hop. Ghostwriters are people who are not credited for making or contributing to a track, enabling the artist to take full credit instead.

A cul-de-sac is a dead end street, often with a circular end, allowing for an easy turn.

ref_text:
Backstroke oversea
 I know what you need
 Already on ten, all money come in
 All feeling go out, this feeling don't drought
 This party won't end
tate_text:
“Backstroke oversea” is a metaphor for drinking alcohol. Kendrick used this metaphor before on his 2012 song, “Swimming Pools”:

Granddaddy had the golden flask, backstroke every day in Chicago

On his song “Sherane a.k.a Master Splinter’s Daughter” from that same year, he raps about performing better in bed when he’s drunk:

And I’m a professional porn star when off the Goose

This line is also figurative for the lengths Lamar will go to for Whitney Alford, his fiancée; he’d literally swim across the ocean for her. The two were high school sweethearts have been together for more than ten years. The “party” is their relationship, and there’s no “drought” because his feelings for her are as strong as ever.

ref_text:
I can see why the fuck I disgust you, I must be
 Allergic to failure, ‘cause everytime I come close to it
 I just sneeze, but I just go achoo then a-chieve!
tate_text:
He has an allergic reaction to failure that causes him to sneeze when he comes close to it. Causes him to go Atchoo (At you) and achieve. Thus fulfilling/achieving his aims.

You can now also see why he disgusts you, because his allergy to failure causes him to go ATCHOO AT YOU. You better get a handkerchief.

Since his allergic symptoms consist of sneezing, the pause after the ‘a’ of the a-llergic is him about to sneeze (a…), but then he catches himself in time to finish the verse.

Achieve (here pronounced atchee) is also a sneezing noise.

It is also worthy of notice that the song ends on the same note it started with : “Being ill”. This might be interpreted as having been the fittest to survive in the rap competition thanks to his illness (dope rapping) in an illmatic sense.

ref_text: [Verse 1]
tate_text: Jay wrote the first verse in about twenty minutes, sitting in the back of the control room. He would just be kind of humming, and we’d keep looping the track, and maybe after thirty minutes he jumped up and was like “We got it!” And he did it ten times, and every time he did it, it was different. Most of the words were the same, but the phrasing was different. He’d written and memorized the words and then was playing with different ways of doing it. It was incredible.

ref_text: [Produced by Kanye West, Evian Christ, Dom Solo, Noah Goldstein, Arca and Mike Dean]
tate_text:
This is a very sexual song with what sound like porn samples, a simple sin/square bass, slowed drum samples and the same distorted one-shot from “Guilt Trip”. During the main section there’s even what sounds like a dog barking sample if you listen carefully. It begins at a very slow 43BPM and pushes up to 120BPM in the main section.

Kilhoffer, one of the album’s producers, said

“I’m in It” started out with a different sample and melody. Then Kanye removed the sample, and it lived as a six-minute arrangement for a while. Then Rick Rubin got ahold of it and structured it to flow as a three-minute piece.

Mike Dean said

[The song] had these crazy guitar parts and all this stadium stuff, and then Rick, Noah, and Kanye pulled it back. I wasn’t very happy with that at first, but it came out really well.

It samples “Lately” by Kenny Lattimore, at the part where he says “a dream”. The sample is pitched and slowed down. You can hear it at 0:33 in the original.

I took a train down memory lane
 And watched little Jermaine do his thing before he made a name
tate_text:
Well, before he was J. Cole…



…he was just little Jermaine

He listened to old Cole before he got a deal and realized he misses the hunger he had, like basquiat (that he mentions in the next lines), who didn’t paint the same when he got signed by Sony (well that’s a picture).

This could be a subtle reference to Nas' chorus from “Memory Lane (Sittin' in Da Park)", as we know in Let Nas Down that Nas deeply inspire him in his raps. At the time of Illmatic (1994), Cole was 9 so he was still a "Lil Jermaine.”

Two of Cole’s biggest role models have done something similar. Hova also “took a trip down memory lane at the cemetery”, talking about the “Gift and the Curse” that Nas refers to in the Let Nas Down remix. That’s a big accumulation of references…

ref_text: Cause I'm such a dreamer, a believer in a sense
tate_text:
These two lines bring to mind an old song from 1967, “Daydream Believer” by The Monkees.

Cheer up, sleepy Jean.
Oh, what can it mean.
To a daydream believer
And a homecoming queen.

A popular interpretation of the song is events after the marriage of a daydream believer and a homecoming queen. Their relationship is unconventional due to different social statuses, but their love gets them through hard times. Sampha could be referring to a relationship with a woman, or a “relationship” with the industry and one’s career.

Another point of reference might be The Dreamer/The Believer, the 2011 album by Common. Interesting that Sampha would drop the reference on Drake’s track, considering the beef war between Com and Drizzy.

I don't care about you, why you worried 'bout me?
 All I want is that smoke, give me all of that smoke
tate_text:
The Weeknd may be coming down or just gluttonously seeking some weed. His tone indicates an attempt at reassuring the audience that he’s not doing anything “serious,” and he further rejects concern by noting he doesn’t care about those who are worrying about him.

However, this dismissal is ironic considering there were 10 drugs referenced in this song – adderall,  alcohol/liquor,  cocaine, marijuana, XO – ecstasy and oxycontin, lean – codeine and promethazine, prescriptions and methamphetamines. Should we not be worried?



Originally, there was fan speculation that this lyric was directed at Drake (and possibly a response to this Drake line), as they were assumed to have fallen out when The Weeknd signed with Universal Records instead of Drake’s label, OVO. However, The Weeknd debunked the rumors that there was ever a beef between the Toronto natives in his Complex interview.

tate_text: Controversy sells records, but it generates interest in news stories as well. The media knows they will get more money off of depicting Eminem as a psychotic thug than a family man, so they overreact to his every move and try to ruin his image. tate_text:
For the outro Beyoncé channels Soulja Boy and borrows from his 2008 single “Turn My Swag On.”

The track was widely successful when it first dropped, selling over a million digital downloads, peaking at No. 3 on the Billboard rap charts and spawning freestyles from Fabolous, Jeezy, Gucci Mane, R. Kelly and Jadakiss; plus a remix with Lil Wayne. The song was also notably covered by the Hive-assumed rival Keri Hilson.

Here, Bey again asserts her flawless-ness confirming how powerful she is and how empowered she feels. This section also serves as a fitting precursor to the entire theme of the next song, “DON’T HURT YOURSELF.”

ref_text:
I'm tryna keep my faith
 But I'm looking for more
 Somewhere I can feel safe
 And end my holy war
 I'm tryna keep my faith
tate_text:
“Holy War” is viewed as a conflict between religions; however, among people of faith it’s more commonly used to describe the struggle between one’s faith in God and the temptation of this world.

When The-Dream talks about being safe, he doesn’t mean being protected against his enemies, he means to be protected against himself. He wants to stop the inner bickering between what’s right and what’s wrong and try to not being controlled by his egotistical self.

In short, he is looking to find his inner peace.

As the intro of “Jesus Walks” says:

We at war
We at war with terrorism, racism
But most of all we at war with ourselves

Between lines “Somewhere I can feel safe” and “And end my holy war” you can hear sample from Counter-Strike, precisely the line ““throwin' flashbang!””. It’s pretty quiet in song, but it’s definitely sampled.

“But I’m Looking for more” refers to the inherently insubstantial nature of religious faith. Faith is not rooted in facts or reasoning, but only in spiritual feeling.

Kanye had previously established a metaphor of Faith as an “Ultra-light beam". Here he further develops that metaphor. The ultralight beam, is insubstantial – it’s light can be seen and it’s warmth can be felt but it has no physical substance.

ref_text:
And I’m never gonna stop until I make ‘em
 Drop and burn ‘em up and scatter their remains,
tate_text:
This couplet (the last “I’m” included) is the phrase in which Lafayette spits out 19 words in an approximately 3 second span, which makes it the fastest set of lyrics in Broadway history, according to FiveThirtyEight, as mentioned in the song’s description.

Daveed Diggs is a veteran of such mind-boggling pace, dealing out some seriously fast verses as an MC in clipping., his LA rap group.

According to LMM’s interview on Stephen Colbert, this line is also intended to show Lafayette’s evolution from a weak English speaker in his first appearance in the show to this point, where his command of English language is the most powerful of anyone in the show.

ref_text: Uh, I think about more than I forget
tate_text:
This line is a truism. It’s impossible not to think about more than you forget.

But apparently that won’t stop Genius from trying to find meaning in it…

The line is perhaps supposed to mean that Wayne holds on to grudges and motivates himself through what he’s been through. He’s more likely to dwell on that stuff than to let it go.
More memories stay with him for him to ruminate over, than fade into the background where they belong.

Another possible interpretation is that he doesn’t forget the way the rest of us forget. We’re always acquiring information that’s only needed in those moments, so we forget it once the time has passed. Wayne’s long memory can be both good and bad: he can hold a grudge, but also appreciates those who have been there for him.

Kendrick is saying if he were to die, his brothers and sisters born afterward would be blessed by having Kendrick’s experiences and wisdom of the dangers and pitfalls in his environment.

ref_text:
‘Cause I don't write shit, ‘cause I ain't got time
 ‘Cause my seconds, minutes, hours go to the almighty dollar
 And the almighty power of that ch-cha-cha-chopper
tate_text:
Important to note that he’s saying he doesn’t write down his lyrics. Not that he doesn’t come up with them himself. But why doesn’t he write? One could understand from these lines that it’s because writing is a non-revenue-generating waste of his time. He’s too busy a) making money, and b) shooting machine guns (commonly refered to as “choppers”).

These lines also contain a religious motif — tablet (10 commandments), sacrificing time to the “almighty” dollar, praising “almighty” power.

I read the things they write about me
 Hear what they're sayin' on the TV, it's crazy
 It's gettin' hard for them to shock me
 But every now and then, it's shocking, don't blame me
 I know it's the life that I chose
 But baby, I'm grateful, I want you to know
 I'm happy for the love and all of the above
 If I'm being honest, I done been through way too much
tate_text:
In December 2018, Ariana received some backlash for trying to promote her track, “imagine,” during a  Kanye West and Drake feud. Moments after Kanye and Ariana’s exchange, her ex-fiance Pete Davidson posted messages that implied he wanted to commit suicide.

Ariana was also called out for appropriating Japanese culture on the cover art and in the music videos for “imagine” and January 2019’s “7 rings.” Interestingly, she had to get her tattoo of Japanese letters covered after finding out it said “small charcoal grill,” instead of the intended phrase “7 rings.”

Finally, after releasing “7 rings,” she was accused of plagiarism by artists like Princess Nokia, who called her out for stealing the concept and flow of her September 2016 track “Mine.” Media and fans also noted the similarities to 2 Chainz’s 2011 track “Spend It.”

Ariana addressed criticism from others on her 2016 track “I Don’t Care”:

Used to cry ‘bout some crazy shit before
I used to feel so obligated to be so much more
I used to let some people tell me how to live and what to be
But if I can’t be me, the fuck’s the point?

tate_text:
This line most likely refers to coming down from drugs. Some drugs, such as cocaine, can change how your body temperature feels.

A bit more far-fetched may be the depressive side-effects of some of the drugs Abel and his girl consumed, such as ecstasy, overnight. They also consumed alcohol for breakfast, so the high could be quickly becoming a depression.

Later in the verse, The Weeknd makes a reference to his aspiration to fly down to Cali, which is a lot warmer than native region Canada.

 Got nowhere to go, put away my pride
 Tired of feeling low even when I'm high
 Ain't no way to live, do I wanna die?
 I don't know, I don't know
 Bells getting loud, ain't nowhere to hide
 Got nowhere to go, put away my pride
 Tired of feeling low even when I'm high
 Ain't no way to live, do I wanna die?
 I don't know, I don't know
tate_text:
Church bells ring when someone dies. The bells getting louder suggests Cole believes his death is growing imminent.

Despite his successes and the typically euphoric effects of marijuana, he can’t escape his depression. He contemplates whether or not he wants to continue living, echoing the sentiment of Hamlet’s “To be, or not to be” soliloquy.

If this song is from the perspective of Cole’s late friend, as so much of this album is, then these lines would link with the album’s closing verse, specifically the moment Cole’s friend speaks with him on the phone:

I’ve been having premonitions
Just call it visions from the other side
I got a feeling I won’t see tomorrow
Like the time I’m living on is borrowed

ref_text: ‘Cause it feels so empty without me
tate_text:
There’s two things Slim is bringing up (that haven’t been mentioned in earlier annotations)

After releasing The Slim Shady LP in 1999 and The Marshall Mathers LP in 2000 – both received by some with serious controversy over lyrical content – Eminem waited a full 2 years to release Without Me as the lead single in 2002.  During those 2 year there were really no musical controversies worth mentioning, and it is this Slim Shady is referring to, with a sly grin no doubt.

Furthermore, music had hit a real lull in 2001, the year without an Eminem album.  Not just for hip hop, but in general.  The top 5 selling albums in 2001 were an aging Michael Jackson, Shaggy, ‘N Sync, Enya(!?) and Staind(!?!?!!).  Not only was the music boring, the musicians really lacked any charisma, humour or distinct personality, the exact opposite for Marshall. When Eminem returned in 2002, he easily filled the void and took the number 1 spot for the entire year.

tate_text:
This is Aaron Burr’s theme song, many other songs with Aaron Burr in them reference this song and it serves to show a difference between Alexander Hamilton and him. In My Shot (Hamilton’s theme song) he doesn’t want to throw away his shot. Aaron Burr is waiting for things to happen and Hamilton is ready to make things happen.

It also shows the difference between Hamilton’s upfront, strong way of showing his opinions and beliefs and Burr’s more subtle, almost invisible way of showing what he cares about.

tate_text:
The double edged sword of fame and fortune: you get rich and popular beyond your wildest dreams, but you also become a lightning rod of attention to critics that want to benefit themselves through attacking you.

Eminem has seen his fair share of lawsuits from attorneys that wanted a turn at him in his early days – he was sued by a former childhood bully of his, accused of defamation by his mother, and put on probation for a pistol whipping case, an event that he references later in the song.

ref_text:
Talent is God-given, be grateful
 Fame is not a given, be humble
 And conceit is self-driven, drive carefully
tate_text:
Wayne rewords a popular quote from John Wooden that cautions against one’s own ego:

Talent is God-given; be humble. Fame is man-given; be grateful. Conceit is self-given; be careful.

Wayne has always openly thanked God, like in his announcement video for Tha Carter V. He’s also made religious tracks like 2007’s “Pray To The Lord.” At many of his concerts, Wayne starts his show with the words “I believe in God”:

https://youtu.be/83kPwzbvtg8?t=1m8s

Additionally, Wayne expresses his gratitude on tracks like 2016’s “Grateful,” and in a 2011 interview with GQ, he explains the importance of being humble:

I was just born to be who I am. I am very humble, and I am very gracious and very grateful for everything that happens to me and about me and around me. So with that said, I wouldn’t be any other way anyways.

ref_text: And they blame it on Marilyn
tate_text:
It has been reported by the students of the Columbine Shooting that the ones who shot up the school (Eric Harris & Dylan Klebold) were fans of American rock band, Marilyn Manson (though this was later proven to be false.)

Since Rock & Roll was introduced to the world, there has always been the theory that music can persuade the type of violent behavior these students committed. The band has been known for it’s arguably reckless, eerie behavior, so it’s no surprise that the public eye held Manson responsible.

It is also possible that this lyric has a much deeper meaning, criticizing the media. When something as horrid as a school shooting occurs, people are quick to point fingers at controversial music artists such as Marilyn Manson or Eminem himself, for influencing a crime that’s completely indirect to them.

Eminem mentioned something similar to this on his song “Who Knew.”

But don’t blame me when little Eric jumps off of the terrace,
you should’ve been watching him.
Apparently, you ain’t parents

By ending with this line from the top of the first two verses, it seems like Drake has an infinite list of things that’ve changed with this girl since he blew up.

The longing for the old times with his girl before he was famous and she got interested in other guys/traveling the world/etc doesn’t stop at the end of the song. It’s almost as if the song is meant to be played on repeat, which in fact it was, for 12 minutes, when Drake premiered it on the the second episode of the OVO Sound show on Beats1 radio on July 25, 2015 (starts around 1:09:35).

Just like the scenarios in the “One of Those Nights” and “Pretty” music videos, Abel literally has somebody’s blood on him. It seems like Ed wasn’t the only person to end up in a fight that night. Perhaps a one-night stand has gone too far, resulting in Abel having to fight a girl’s lover. He’s made it known that “XO niggas, ain’t nothing to mess with.”

He’s coming down from a recent cocaine session. “Dripping throat” is a term for excess cocaine that passes the sinuses and goes into the throat, the drip has little intoxicating effect. He lights a cigarette after this apparent scuffle and realizes that this is the life that he chose.

ref_text:
I’m a little nervous, but I can’t show it
 I’m sorry, I’m a Hamilton with pride
 You talk about my father, I cannot let it slide
tate_text:
The first two lines of this verse are exactly the same as nine-year-old Philip’s, creating a callback. These next three are not exactly the same, but they’re constructed in parallel, with a similar structure of rhymes, repeated sounds, and antonym pairs. And yet the verse in this song is much more sophisticated and adult, with longer lines, more apt word choices, and better rhythm with fewer pauses and filler words. Compare:


I wrote this poem just to show it.
I’m a little nervous but I can’t show it.

And I just turned nine
I’m sorry, I’m a Hamilton with pride

You can write rhymes but you can’t write mine!
You talk about my father, I cannot let it slide!


The overall effect is: Little Philip has grown up. Philip only spends a few minutes on stage, so Miranda doesn’t have much time to make us fall in love with him. With five lines in “Take A Break” and five more here, he makes us feel the same mix of nostalgia, joy, pride, and love that Philip’s parents feel every time they look at him.

All so that, when Philip gets shot a minute or two later, it breaks our hearts just as it breaks theirs.

ref_text: [Death to Molly]
tate_text:
In the “Bitch Don’t Kill My Vibe” music video, the string ensemble that plays during the outro is cut off with a black shot with the text: Death to Molly.



Molly is the purest form of ecstasy, usually given as a free powder or contained in a capsule. MDMA is consistently mentioned in contemporary rap, be it most humorously referenced by Trinidad James in the legendary:

Popped a Molly I’m sweating (woo!)

However it has also got artists in hot water, on Rocko’s “U.O.E.N.O.”, which features rapper Rick Ross, he rhymes:

Put Molly all in her champagne, she ain’t even know it
I took her home and I enjoyed that, she ain’t even know it"

Ross, who also remixed this Kendrick classic, has had his endorsement deal with Reebok dropped as as result of these lyrics.

Kendrick spoke on wanting to kill the Molly trend in hip-hop:

Sometimes you have the trends that’s not that cool. You may have certain artists portraying these trends and don’t really have that lifestyle and then it gives off the wrong thing. And it becomes kinda corny after a while. When everybody consciously now uses this term or this phrase and putting it in lyrics, it waters the culture down. So it’s really just time to move on. It’s really about keeping hip-hop original and pushing away the corniness in it.
