ref_text: I'm talkin' fear, fear of losin' creativity
tate_text:
Two of the biggest fears for an artist is the self-doubt of not being good enough to continue their craft and the feeling of not bringing anything new or original to the world. A 2017 article posed the question: “Is it Better for Legends to Burn Out or Fade Away?” The article specifically talked about legendary rappers Rakim, Nas, and André 3000 from OutKast—three of Kendrick’s Top 10 rappers of all-time, as he told Erykah Badu when she interviewed him in 2013 for Interview Magazine.

While Rakim is regarded as “the God MC” who influenced many rap legends that came after him, his ability to create hits through the 1990s faded when the tides of hip-hop shifted away from him as the genre was becoming more mainstream. Nas took the torch from Rakim in the ‘90s but he has millennials trying to fade him out by saying “nobody listens to Nas anymore” in today’s industry full of “lil” auto-tuned rappers. André 3000, on the other hand, has essentially burned out on making music and is semi-retired, saying the following to Complex in 2017:

I kind of like not being a part of [rap], now that I’ve done it. As I get older, I start to see myself move more back from it — the hustle and bustle of putting out an album, the pressure of being in the studio trying to come up with something. Now it’s more like a hobby for me, so I don’t think about it in that way. […] Do I really want to be 50 years old up there doing that? When I watch other rappers that are my age I commend them, but I just wonder where the inspiration is coming from. At this stage, I’m really more focused on what I am going to be doing 10 years from now, and I hope to God it won’t be rapping.

Kendrick wants to bow out of the rap game gracefully on his own terms but he neither wants to question himself nor would he want people questioning him on if he’s still got it in him to cultivate continuous creativity. In a 2018 interview with Billboard, Kendrick had a similar take to André 3000 on when he feels it’s his time to step aside:

It’s really always having love for it, and really having fun with it. I think the moment when I’m not having fun with it, and getting into the studio and—you know, going back to the Kobe [Bryant] similarities—maxing out on the full potential, that’s when the fumbling happens. Before that even happens, I’d pass it down and give it to another young boy that has that same passion that can carry that [throne]. But right now, I feel good. I’ll let y'all know when the final years is coming up.

ref_text: [Produced by DJ Frank E, Kanye West & Mike Dean]
tate_text:
“Blame Game” is built around a recreation of Aphex Twin’s track “Avril 14th”. The track starts off with John Legend singing an introduction lasting a minute. The record’s production is lush and cello-driven with predominant piano. It has a very soulful sound while Ye’s lyrics and voice varies between angry and subsequently less antagonistically and repeatedly confesses Kanye’s forceful deliver and expresses hurt and contempt. At times like a ballad:

I can’t love you this much

West’s vocals are considerably distorted throughout the track, from naturally clear-sounding and ominously pitched-down as it pans left and right as they are sped up, slowed down, edited substantially, and altered in various ways, giving the song a ominous and brooding mood. The effect is almost psychotic, suggesting three or four inner monologues fighting over smashed emotions.

Books were not easily obtained or common in St. Croix.  Hamilton was voracious for anything he could read:

Like Ben Franklin, Hamilton was mostly self-taught and probably snatched every spare moment to read. The young clerk aimed to be a man of  letters. He may already have had a premonition that his facility with words would someday free him from his humble birth and place him on a par with the most powerful men of his age.

He hit the book jackpot when a minister named Hugh Knox let Hamilton into his personal library.

We do not know exactly how they met, but Knox threw open his library to this prodigious youth, encouraged him to write verse, and prodded him toward scholarship.

ref_text: [Verse 2]
tate_text:
In an interview with NPR, Mike WiLL-Made It revealed that Kendrick recorded this verse a cappella and asked him to build the beat around it:

With “DNA.,” he went the whole way [through] and then he just started rapping a cappella. He said, ‘I just want to see if you can put some drums around this.’ I said, ‘Man, hell yeah.’ But he was going so hard; that man was rapping so crazy. Just imagine him a cappella rapping the second half of “DNA.” and I had to build a beat around that. I didn’t want the beat to just sound like a regular boom-clap, boom-clap. I wanted that shit to sound just as crazy. I wanted it to sound like he’s battling the beat.

Also note that throughout this verse that you can hear someone shouting “gimme some ganja!” continuously in the background. This sample comes from the deceased American musician and composer Rick James performance of Mary Jane live, where he shouts “gimme some ganja!” on stage:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IVxatH_VyQo

Sampling an influential American legend also plays into one of the themes of “DNA” – celebrating black heritage and the major accomplishments African-Americans have made within the music industry.

ref_text: Backin' out the parkin' spot and though the law be on him
tate_text:
This is a reference to racial profiling in America and how African-Americans are stereotyped to be criminals or bad people. Cole criticizes the corruption in the police system as African-Americans are harassed, injured, and even killed for actions that are perceived as legal for other races. For example, in 2014, Michael Brown was shot to death by a white police officer in Missouri as a result of a confrontation based on Brown being charged with a robbery. This event strengthened the Black Lives Matter movement, a movement designed to combat racial inequality and police corruption against Africans.

J. Cole has been known to be an avid supporter of Black Lives Matter and other racial protests; he dedicated a song, “Be Free”, towards Ferguson’s death in addition to touching this idea on songs such as “Neighbors”.

ref_text: Awesome. Wow
tate_text:
George insultingly utilizes the American accent. He also uses words that commonly are used by sarcastic teenagers who most pointedly DO NOT think whatever they are talking about is awesome.

It’s a fun anachronism, too, since during this period, the standard English and American accents were largely the same—in fact, they were both closer to the American accent we hear today. The British accent as we know it now (called “Received Pronunciation”) disseminated largely in the 19th century. So George’s “Awesome, wow”—for all its mocking, Valley Girl sensibility—is actually be closer to his true accent at the time.

ref_text:
I put my hand on a stove, to see if I still bleed, yeah
 And nothing hurts anymore, I feel kinda free
tate_text:
This refers to the psychology behind self-harm. Whilst some people self-harm to punish themselves, others do it because they feel emotionally numb—they inflict pain on themselves in order to feel alive again.

“I feel kinda free” might relate to the euphoria some people experience from self-harm. When we experience pain, endorphins are released into the bloodstream, resulting in a natural high or a feeling of euphoria.

Kanye has dealt with depression himself and has been very public about how painful his mother’s death has been to him.

Went through, deep depression when my mama passed
Suicide, what kinda talk is that?



In an interview with Rolling Stone, soon after the release of the album, 070 Shake explained the lyric as a feeling of numbness to the sensation of pain:

If you burn it a lot, burn it hard enough, you will actually bleed. A lot of people asked me about that line: “Do you know what a stove is?” Bro, if you burn it for long enough, you’re going to bleed. It gets to the point where it’s so numb that you don’t even feel it. When it bleeds, it’s so numb that you don’t even feel it. It was a whole metaphor.

ref_text:
And I come in peace to compete
 I don't run if you'd rather leap, my statistics go up in weeks
tate_text:
Kendrick says he’s coming into the rap game in peace, but contradicts this in saying “to compete.” It’s a similar mentality to the one presented in his “Control” verse:

But this is hip-hop, and them niggas should know what time it is
And that goes for Jermaine Cole, Big K.R.I.T., Wale
Pusha T, Meek Millz, A$AP Rocky, Drake
Big Sean, Jay Electron', Tyler, Mac Miller
I got love for you all, but I’m tryna murder you niggas

Kendrick’s humbling himself, but don’t take his kindness for weakness; he’s still here to compete. “I don’t run if you’d rather leap” assures this, as he’s able to adjust to any style of competition you prefer.

He’s got the statistics to prove it too. He’s dropped a platinum album, the fastest-selling album of 2017, a surprise project that skyrocketed to #1 on the Billboard 100 and more.

ref_text: Just remember, what happens on Earth stays on Earth!
tate_text:
Kid Capri also dropped this line on “ELEMENT.”  It’s an adaption of the phrase “what happens in Vegas, stays in Vegas,” but also alludes to the Bible verse 1 Timothy 6:7:

For we brought nothing into this world, and it is certain we can carry nothing out.

Kid Capri also annotated this line on “ELEMENT.,” saying:

To tell the truth, I never asked Kendrick the meaning of it. I said what I said and I never asked him the meaning. He told me to say that part.

The most interesting detail about this line is that Kendrick considered titling the album “What Happens on Earth Stays on Earth,” as stated in an interview with Big Boy.

ref_text: Get down, never lay down
tate_text:
This line refers to the saying “Get Down, or Lay Down”. Drake is saying that it’s never a choice when it comes to getting down for the crew, he is always prepared and ready to do whatever it takes. There’s no laying down when it comes to the crew.

He’ll “break down everyone” to get down for the crew.

ref_text: Refund checks, used that to float
tate_text:
A refund check is something many college students receive once a semester granted the amount of their loans and grants outweigh the amount it costs to attend school.

Being that Cole already told us he is bad with money earlier in the song and was living on his own in NYC, it is safe to assume that he would use this money in order to survive from day to day while away from home.

ref_text: My city love me like Mac Dre in the Bay
tate_text:
Mac Dre is a legendary rapper representing the city of Vallejo in the northern region of the San Francisco Bay Area. From maintaining his status as an independent artist throughout his career and recording albums from a prison pay phone to being a pioneer of the Thizz Movement and personification of the Hyphy Movement prior to his passing in 2004, Mac Dre had a major impact on the substance and style of the Bay Area hip-hop culture—as Bay Area rapper G-Eazy discussed in a 2014 interview with HipHopDX:

Mac Dre means everything to Hip-Hop in the Bay. Mac Dre is more than a legend. He just had such a big like catalog of these mixtapes and albums. He had so much music. So it was like, when Mac Dre really, really, really caught on, which was around the time he died unfortunately, that was when everyone really got swept up into it. He was the biggest force in the Bay.

Drake also paid respect to Dre on “The Motto,” which appears later in the Take Care tracklist—in 2016, Dre’s mom told Rolling Stone how these shout-outs inspired her to make a documentary on her son’s life:

I met with Drake in San Francisco and we sat down and he talked with me about how Mac Dre impacted his life and his career, what he’s doing and the big impact that Mac Dre had when Drake was a young boy. So listening to that, it kind of opened up my eyes that maybe I do need to do this. If Andre was alive he would definitely be capitalizing and making as much money as he could.

Whether it be Toronto City Councillors supporting Drake during the beef he had with Meek Mill, or Toronto radio stations playing him more than any other artist, Toronto always gives love back to Drake—just like Bay Area hip-hop fans supported Mac Dre.



Drake with Toronto Politician Norm Kelly, a supporter of Drake during the Meek x Drake beef

Mayo and went from Hellmann's and being rail thin
 Filet-o-Fish, Scribble Jam, Rap Olympics '97 Freaknik
tate_text:
Hellmann’s is a brand of mayonnaise and McDonald’s Filet-o-Fish is a cheap sandwich. “Mayo” is also a derogatory term used to describe white people. In fact, Charlamagne Tha God, whom Eminem mentioned on “The Ringer,” often uses “mayonnaise” to describe white people he thinks are racists.

Eminem is talking about advancing in his career. He went from being a poor dad to attending big time hip-hop festivals like Scribble Jam and placing second in the ‘97 Rap Olympics. The Rap Olympics was the turning point in his career, as a demo tape handed out during this event ended up in the hands of Jimmy Iovine and Dr. Dre from Interscope Records:

https://youtu.be/DkALZe31QPQ

Freaknik was a large event held in Atlanta, Georgia, from 1983 to 1999, which consisted mostly of students from historically black universities.

ref_text:
When raindrops fell
 Down from the sky
 The day you left me
 An angel cried
 Oh, she cried, an angel cried
 She cried
tate_text:
Although this is a cover of the last verse of The Four Season’s “An Angel Cried,” these lyrics can be connected to the May 2017 bombing at Ariana’s Dangerous Woman Tour in Manchester, England. 22 concertgoers were killed, and several others were injured.

The attack is mentioned several times throughout the album, and “get well soon” even ends with a forty-second silence to honor the victims. This silence brings the track’s length to 5:22, to commemorate the bombing date, May 22nd.

tate_text:
The sample comes from Shiloh Dynasty’s “Don’t Go To Sleep”:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7Uws4pZ7tDo

This line may be from the perspective of a loved one (or even his inner voice) telling him to not commit suicide, but to live, which in this case is compared to “staying awake,” while “going to sleep” means leaving your problems to others, by ending your life.

It could also show how lonely and empty X feels to the point where sleep isn’t an escape and he just wants someone up with him to reassure him.

ref_text: Magnolia Shorty
tate_text:
This is a sample from Magnolia Shorty’s 2010 track, “Smoking Gun,” which in turn sampled Jadakiss' 2009 track of the same name. Magnolia’s version exemplifies an authentic New Orleans sound, known as Bounce, and the sample here also serves as homage to Magnolia Shorty, Drake’s former labelmate at Cash Money Records, who was murdered in 2010.



Magnolia, right, standing with Cash Money founder and fellow New Orleans rapper, Birdman.

“Trade” is New Orleans slang for men who’re handsome and have money.

Hidden conflict or competitiveness within an organization.

This also foreshadows Washington’s warning against partisan fighting as he mentions in “One Last Time”. After all, are two political parties so different to two armies?

tate_text:
Hollywood, Florida, in Broward County, is an area close to where X grew up. X is likely reminiscing about the period of time when he didn’t have his own place, so he stayed at motels with his ex-girlfriend, Geneva.

“Hell, I think I’m just obsessed with you,” could refer to someone’s inability to recognize the harm they feel in a relationship because you only focus on being in love.

Hell could also be a personification of his ex-girlfriend, or at least the emotions she brought him.

If you go to heaven and they bring me to hell
 Just sneak out and meet me,
tate_text:
Beyoncé’s love is total. The intimation is that they will die together, and with Jay’s dark past and his wife’s perfection, chances are he’ll be stuck downstairs in the afterlife.

As a true ride or die girl, Beyoncé wouldn’t hesitate to sneak her man some marijuana (an L is a marijuana joint).

This also resurrects one of Jay’s earliest recorded punchlines. On his famous “7 Minute Freestyle” with Big L, Jay rapped:

Even if they won’t let me in Heaven, I raise hell, till it’s Heaven

In this instance, the marijuana will get him high enough to ascend from the depths of hell to the awaiting arms of his girl in heaven.

Catch me, don't you—
 Catch me, don't you catch me
 I've fallen in love for the first time
 I wanna cry
 And I ain't even tryna fight it
tate_text:
J. Cole’s love songs usually revolve around these two topics:


Being him not being able to obtain the girl he wants, like in “03' Adolescence”, “Power Trip” and “Dreams”.
Him just wanting to have sex like in “Wet Dreamz”.



This is one of the very first songs that he has dove deeper in to the meaning of true love.

He is showing himself as an exposed person, he has fallen in love and he doesn’t care that he is vulnerable; he isn’t trying to “fight it”.

ref_text: If I quit your BM, I still ride Mercedes, funk
tate_text:
Kendrick plays on “BM” to mean “baby mother” and German car manufacturer BMW. Mercedes-Benz is another German luxury car manufacturer and a popular female name derived from the Spanish, “Merced”—no matter what, Kendrick will ride with a woman and in style. He spit a similar BMW/BM line on 2010’s “Look Out For Detox”:

I’m being myself, my BFF is a BM-dub
With your BM in it and your stash box glove

This line also draws similarities to Pimp C’s line on Big Pimpin':

If I wasn’t rappin', baby, I would still be ridin' Mercedes

ref_text: In trouble waters I had to learn how to float
tate_text:
Hov is referring to his rough upbringing in his early years. His childhood home was the Marcy Projects, and as mentioned in the previous line, he was a crack dealer. The Marcy projects are the “trouble water” where he had to sell crack to survive (stay “afloat”). Hov had to turn his life around, culminating in the 1996 release of his debut album, Reasonable Doubt.



Today, Hov is one of the most successful musicians/businessmen in America, with an estimated net worth of $500 million. He has ventured into the world of sports as well as clothing, has a stable family, and has certainly learned “how to float.”



Troubled water recalls John 5:4

For an angel went down at a certain season into the pool, and troubled the water: whosoever then first after the troubling of the water stepped in was made whole of whatsoever disease he had.

Jay-Z went through the troubled waters (A metaphor for his drug dealing past) and came out of them clean, able to float, just like Jesus. He’s the God MC after all, isn’t he?

ref_text:
Aw man… where is she takin' me?
 Where is she takin' me?
tate_text:
This part is the transition from the party style atmosphere of the earlier half of the song to the philosophical commentary on drinking in general. He is possibly torn by two “shes,” one being a woman at the party that Kendrick’s conscious is trying to get him to sober up enough to have a good time with, the other alcohol in general. The question where is she taking me leads to wondering both physically where she is dragging him, but also where his life is going to end up if he continues living his life like this

The deepened voice presented here is to show the drunkedness of Kendrick Lamar, how his blood alcohol content has reached such a peak as to cause his voice to slur, and his senses to be disoriented as well as making him lose control of his actions.



Right before this section, during Sherraaaneee the bridge plays again, in the same slowed-down drunken slur. The “dive in” sounds a lot like “slide in”, insinuating that Sherane has seduced Kendrick. This is also supported by the “Aw man, where is she taking me?” bar.

It’s a very hippie attitude. Jay’s dislike for the boys in blue (police) is well known, and he compares their relentless pursuit of him to that of gossip sites and paparazzi, with their rumour-mongering.

Peace. They don’t care.

ref_text: [Verse 2: Eminem]
tate_text:
This song spawned the phrase of “renegading” someone. It was popularized by Nas – in “Ether”:

And Eminem murdered you on your own shit

That even though the song was for Jay-Z’s album, Eminem destroyed him on it or “renegaded” him. To be renegaded is when you feature someone on your track and they completely outclass you.

In an interview with Rosenberg Radio Jay Z admitted that Eminem had the better verse. His defense was in the essence that every dog has its day and that he has had the better verse on the majority of his songs. Blaming Nas for the phenomena that people wonders who murdered who before the record is already released and debate afterward who bodied who –  instead of just enjoying the song. He also admitted it in “A Star Is Born”:

His flow on Renegade, fucking awesome
Applaud him

Numerous artists, critics and fans have praised Eminems verses on this song – including Talib Kweli who called this his “3rd favorite Hip Hop verse of all time”.

The verse is exceptional as said by various artists and this rhyme scheme highlights the complexity of the verse.



In 2014 Eminem rapped this verse over Jay’s “Run This Town” at the “The Monster Tour”:
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lXjOs9dBgoI

Andre Gainer from Lyricology 101 deconstructs the rhyme schemes, flows and performance in the verse:
https://youtu.be/_EIefzGnk3I?t=2m38s

ref_text: [Produced by J. Cole & Nate Jones]
tate_text:
As J. Cole and Nas spit the first four bars of “Nas Is Like” together it symbolizes a passing of the tourch/he is the new Nas as Nas begins, while J. Cole finished the classic line.

The saxophone melody carries the track, but the boom bap gives it a special hip hop feel, as if it is bridging eras. The message on the song is the focus, as Cole delivers one of his bravest efforts of his career as he tells the story of Nas hearing his first single, “Work Out.”

The song contains two samples. The saxophone riff is from “Gentleman” as performed by Fela Kuti:
http://youtu.be/snIV_-IECsM?t=1m13s
While the Nas vocals are sampled from “Nas Is Like”:

Freedom or jail, clip’s inserted, a baby’s being born
Same time a man is murdered, the beginning and end
As far as rap go, it’s only natural I explain
My plateau, and also, what defines my name

ref_text: [Chorus: James Fauntleroy]
tate_text:
I’ve known Terrace and a huge percentage of the people involved in the album for probably ten years now. That’s why I was even called. They just called me and asked if I would come by and sing on the thing. I went in there, came up with what I wanted to sing. It was just so natural. Did it really fast, got really high. It was unbelievable. I’ll never forget going in there and hearing that music. It’s one of the best albums of my adult life and of my career. It’s one of the best things i’ve heard and been a part of. For it to be so deserving and acknowledged by the president was an all-around amazing experience.

After this president, there probably won’t be another that listens to rap music. The fact that we have a president that listens to rap publicly, that he listens to this amazing album that should’ve won album of the year, and that his favorite song is my song on the album—it’s insane. It’s not an award, it’s not a plaque, it’s not a dollar amount. There’s nothing that is like the leader of the free world lying around on Air Force One listening to To Pimp a Butterfly and having my song come on and be like “turn that one up.”

 Fifteen, scrapin' up his jeans with quarter pieces

tate_text:
“Clocking grips” usually means to make money, but Kendrick may be using “grip” to mean gun.

Anthony had a gun and was slangin'/drug dealing at the age of 15. A “quarter piece” is a synonymous term for seven grams of cocaine, a quarter ounce.

Anthony’s initiation into gang life is the culmination of family influences described in lines just before.

It is a very common practice for drug dealers to give drugs in exchange for sexual favors. Anthony was receiving oral sex from a crack addict.

tate_text:
The autotuned warble is an intentional trick of Kanye’s, used to great effect on the “Runaway” outro.

The phrase “summer rose” may refer to the poem “The Last Rose of Summer” by Thomas Moore. This wouldn’t be the first poem interpolated in this song, nor the first plant (following poplar trees and magnolias). The rose in the title is generally understood as a metaphor for the hopelessness of heartbreak; all the other roses have died, and the narrator plucks the rose to save it from its loneliness:

Thus kindly I scatter,
Thy leaves o'er the bed,
Where thy mates of the garden
Lie scentless and dead.

tate_text:
Love is reflected when two people make a mutual effort to stay together and sometimes that effort might be through arguments and fights.

Yet occasional “warring” is healthy and you only lose the relationship when no one cares enough to fight back and work out the problems.

“On the floor” could mean the make up sex they have after that.

ref_text: Look around, look around at how lucky we are to be alive right now!
tate_text:
Eliza’s theme is introduced here, and it recurs in both word and melody several times throughout the show. Eliza and Alexander both sing this phrase to each other at different points in the story. Musically this recurs in “Schuyler Defeated” as “Further down, further down.”

This line is also an important tie between the past being depicted on stage, and the present being experienced by the audience. In a sense, Miranda is saying to the viewer/listener: look at what these people experienced, and the actions they took, and try to understand how lucky we are to live in the country they created for us.

At this stage of the musical, Eliza is referring to being lucky because of the progress and enlightenment in this time period. In “That Would Be Enough”, she repeats it in reference to surviving the war, when so many have died.

ref_text:
(If you really believe it, gotta talk about it
 You heard about what happens when you talk about it
tate_text:
Cole has been very vocal about the recent struggle between African Americans and white policemen, and it’s possible that this line plays on that. His song “Be Free” is short but graphic; a famous man making a blatant, conscious, essential statement.

“Remaining silent in the face of injustice is the same as supporting it”. Yet when you do speak out, there can be deadly consequences. You may even be labeled a “conscious” rapper, which can limit your mainstream appeal.

But, as Tupac Shakur stated:

That’s our job, It’s to spark somebody else watching us. We might not be the one’s, but let’s not be selfish and because we not gonna change the world let’s not talk about how we should change it. I don’t know how to change it, but I know if I keep talking about how dirty it is out here, somebody’s gonna clean it up.

On a more surface level, Cole is probably expressing anxiety about sharing his goals with other people.

When you share what you believe with others, they sometimes look at you funny because they’re doubting you and that can lead to you doubting yourself. In the end, he says that you still “gotta talk about it” or those goals might never be accomplished.

ref_text:
He knows just what it does
 When he’s holding me tight
 And he calls me "Moonlight" too
tate_text:
The ending lyrics amplify the emotion of the  track, saying that this boy is displaying her his love and affection by calling her moonlight, at which up until this point Grande has only said to him. They hold each other tight in true happiness, hoping the night will never end.



Victoria Monét, one of Grande’s close friends and writers for the album, can be seen stating that “Moonlight” was what Ricky Alvarez, Ariana’s ex boyfriend, called her after their first kiss.

ref_text:
‘Cause I'm a renegade!
 Never been afraid to talk about anything
 (Anything?) Anything! (Anything)
tate_text:
He has no qualms rapping about anything, no matter how offensive society considers it.

Both Jay-Z and Eminem have made many songs that either challenged social order or drew criticism for being downright offensive.

Examples include:
-99 Problems
-Mosh
-3 a.m.
-Hard Knock Life (Ghetto Anthem)
-Kill You

The way Jay-Z questions “anything?” after Em says “anything”, is an allusion to Jay’s song Anything. The chorus sampled in Jay’s song sounds just like Em in Renegade.
http://youtu.be/odThhIA2gUM?t=1m26s

 This line may also echoes the refrain from Oliver Twist in which the Artful Dodger reconfirms he would do anything for love.

Jay Z and Eminem are like the Artful Dodger – they’re devoted and would do anything and say anything. Like Em and Jay, The Artful Dodger grew up on the streets and had to make his own way.

Check it out at 1:19 and 4:44 here:
https://youtu.be/ey0D53Dxl3M

Jay Z might also be familiar with the character and story seeing as in 2007 he bought the luxury clothing brand, Artful Dodger. It also wouldn’t be the first reference to musicals (see Hard Knock Life).

ref_text: [Part I: 0 to 100]
tate_text:
This song was allegedly supposed to be Diddy’s but Frank Dukes shared it with Boi-1da and Drake ended up making the song. In an interview with Noisey, Frank Dukes stated:

I just kinda wrote it and gave it to Boi-1da, who was in session at the time in Miami, this was with Diddy. This was like the whole controversy of the incident. From what I understand he made the beat on the spot, played it for Diddy and Diddy passed on it, he said it wasn’t life changing enough and that was that.”

Afterwards Drake crafted the song and the superfluous beef with Diddy and Drake began. Be sure to check out the full analysis made by TMZ.

ref_text: Raise a glass to freedom
tate_text:
Perhaps a reference to “Drink with Me” from Les Miserables, where a similar group of war-bound men toast to their youth and the promise of a better future.

Of course, coming from the fervent abolitionst John Laurens, he may also be asking his friends to “raise a glass to freedom” for slaves.

ref_text: Shoppin' bags, I'm a tourist, nigga
tate_text:
It’s not uncommon for a tourist to shop when on vacation, and of course Rick Ross has Money Bags to spend. He can just enjoy his time in Europe shopping and blowing some money!

Most of the luxury brands that rappers idolize come from Europe. The rich from all around the world come to Europe to buy the best in luxury brands:


France: Louis Vuitton, Cartier, YSL, Louboutin etc.
Italy: Gucci, Prada, Fendi, Dolce & Gabbana etc.
UK: Burberry, Manolo, Jimmy Choo, Alexander McQueen etc.
Switzerland: Audemars Piguet, Rolex, Bally, Hublot etc.



By shopping in Europe, Rick Ross is implying that he’s actually spending a lot of money on luxury brands, not just rapping about it.

Since he is a tourist, Europe is far from home. Knowing the struggle most black people from poor backgrounds have, Rick could also be implying as a “tourist” he shouldn’t even be there with the circumstances he has faced in life. But since he is there, he may as well ball.

ref_text: And the Schuyler sisters are the envy of all
tate_text:
In a letter from Hamilton to Eliza dated March 17, 1780, he wrote that

If I were not afraid of making you vain, I would tell you that Mrs. Carter, Peggy, and yourself are the dayly toasts of our table; and for this honor you are chiefly indebted to the British Gentlemen; though as I am always thinking of you, this naturally brings Peggy to my mind who is generally my toast. Capt Beebe is here and talks of her sometimes; but I won’t give my consent to his being her favourite.

Note that Mrs. Carter refers to Angelica, as one of her husband, “the British Gentleman,” John Church’s wartime aliases was John Carter. It wouldn’t do for the men to seem too proud of their own sweethearts, but Hamilton teasingly mentions to Eliza that they can’t help speaking fondly of the sisters as a unit.

I need that black card and the code to the safe
 Code to the safe, code-code to the safe-safe
tate_text:
The American Express Centurion Card, informally known as the Black Card, is an invite only charge card.



 American Express only issues these cards to members after they have met a variety of criteria. The $7,500 initiation fee has been enough to make the Black Card a symbol of wealth and prosperity, as it offers members features such as 24/7 concierge service and an unlimited spend limit.

This for my niggas that was tossed in the graves
 Every so often I fade deep in my thoughts
 And then get lost in the days
 We used to play before your coffin was made
 Just got the call nigga got caught with a stray
 Hope he's okay
tate_text:
Cole previously spoke of losing his friends on “Knock Tha Hustle” and now reminisces about when they were still alive. His wordplay with “days”—which sounds similar to “daze”—further illustrates how much these losses affect him.



The mentioning of his friend getting shot fits well within the song since Cole later refers to the Ferguson case in verse two.

ref_text: Please don't hit my phone if it ain't 'bout no commas
tate_text:
To “hit someone up” is a common slang phrase for contacting a person. J. Cole uses a similar phrase here, saying not to “hit” his phone, meaning he doesn’t want anyone to text or call him unless it’s about “commas.” This refers to large amounts of money, because a numerical amount in standard English is required to be marked with commas that separate hundreds, thousands, millions, and so forth.



Therefore, larger amounts of money will have more commas in them.
This line plays off the last line, where Jermaine talks about doubling his money and items.

J. Cole’s net worth at the time of the song’s release was estimated to be a little higher than $15 million.

ref_text:
[HAMILTON]
 What?
tate_text:
This is the first time Hamilton says “What?” He says this… a lot. Six times in one musical. Some of this can be read at face value: the hot-head Hamilton doesn’t often listen to others, and he’s often incredulous when he does.

It can also be read in the hip-hop sense. MCs in hip-hop use “what” as a way of amping up a song; it’s like saying “I can’t hear you” to get a crowd or rapper to be louder. Hamilton’s energy is relentlessly driving the story forward. He and the ensemble are the only people who say “what?” in this way. The singular exception is Jefferson in The Adams Administration and The Reynolds Pamphlet, which are also two of the only songs where Jefferson, rather than Hamilton, is driving the action forward.
